00:01:34.080 --> 00:01:38.100
The environment forum
has a particular purpose.

00:01:38.100 --> 00:01:42.240
When Ian and I approached
Professor Bhabha with the idea

00:01:42.240 --> 00:01:46.290
for the forum, we were not
content with the notion

00:01:46.290 --> 00:01:52.230
of sprinkling some humanist
ideas into conversations

00:01:52.230 --> 00:01:54.090
around the environment.

00:01:54.090 --> 00:01:56.490
We wanted to bring
the environment

00:01:56.490 --> 00:02:02.040
to the center of conversations
about what the humanities might

00:02:02.040 --> 00:02:03.240
be.

00:02:03.240 --> 00:02:07.050
The aim was not to include the
environment in the humanities

00:02:07.050 --> 00:02:10.979
as one more topic
or theme, but rather

00:02:10.979 --> 00:02:14.010
to ask what happens
to the humanities

00:02:14.010 --> 00:02:17.280
when one takes the
immensely challenging

00:02:17.280 --> 00:02:19.350
environmental conditions
under which we

00:02:19.350 --> 00:02:25.750
live as a pressing and
critical fact of human life.

00:02:25.750 --> 00:02:28.030
I've been speaking
of the environment,

00:02:28.030 --> 00:02:32.110
but of course there are many
overlapping environments

00:02:32.110 --> 00:02:34.570
that touch human
lives differently,

00:02:34.570 --> 00:02:39.880
depending on social relations
and material circumstances.

00:02:39.880 --> 00:02:44.800
Wealth and privilege offer
buffers from the consequences

00:02:44.800 --> 00:02:47.470
of environmental
disruption, which

00:02:47.470 --> 00:02:51.730
is incurred largely in the
production of that wealth

00:02:51.730 --> 00:02:53.020
and privilege.

00:02:53.020 --> 00:02:55.570
While poverty,
discrimination, and abjection

00:02:55.570 --> 00:03:00.880
bring many forms of
exposure and vulnerability.

00:03:00.880 --> 00:03:03.010
In launching the
environment forum,

00:03:03.010 --> 00:03:06.070
questions of environmental
justice, as well as

00:03:06.070 --> 00:03:11.440
questions about where theory
hits lived experience,

00:03:11.440 --> 00:03:15.720
were very much on our minds.

00:03:15.720 --> 00:03:18.510
From the start, Ian
and I have wanted

00:03:18.510 --> 00:03:21.570
this to be an
inclusive venture built

00:03:21.570 --> 00:03:25.800
on an ever widening circle
of students and faculty

00:03:25.800 --> 00:03:30.660
interested in the intersection
between humanistic questions,

00:03:30.660 --> 00:03:35.580
broadly defined, and
environmental issues.

00:03:35.580 --> 00:03:39.690
One colleague with whom we
knew we wanted to collaborate

00:03:39.690 --> 00:03:42.990
was Ajanta
Subermanian, professor

00:03:42.990 --> 00:03:47.310
of anthropology and
South Asian studies.

00:03:47.310 --> 00:03:51.450
And this gathering,
this event on Scales

00:03:51.450 --> 00:03:54.990
of Environmental Justice,
Building A Transformative

00:03:54.990 --> 00:04:00.660
Politics, is in every
profound way her event.

00:04:00.660 --> 00:04:03.510
And we are so grateful
for the vision and energy

00:04:03.510 --> 00:04:07.670
that she has brought
to putting it together.

00:04:07.670 --> 00:04:11.030
With that I will turn over the
task of further introductions

00:04:11.030 --> 00:04:11.660
to her.

00:04:11.660 --> 00:04:14.908
So please join me in welcoming
Ajanta to the podium.

00:04:14.908 --> 00:04:17.836
[APPLAUSE]

00:04:23.692 --> 00:04:26.170
This is not conducive
to short people.

00:04:26.170 --> 00:04:29.020
[LAUGHTER]

00:04:32.820 --> 00:04:36.180
Thank you Robin for that.

00:04:36.180 --> 00:04:40.480
So this event has been a
long time in the making.

00:04:40.480 --> 00:04:47.080
And I'm delighted to have all
of my fellow panelists here.

00:04:47.080 --> 00:04:50.900
So scales of
environmental justice.

00:04:50.900 --> 00:04:53.330
These are urgent times.

00:04:53.330 --> 00:04:56.000
We're witnessing the
rise of authoritarianism

00:04:56.000 --> 00:04:59.480
and ethonationalist
politics the world over.

00:04:59.480 --> 00:05:02.090
In the United States, the
election of Donald Trump

00:05:02.090 --> 00:05:05.870
has ushered in more
tolerance for overt racism,

00:05:05.870 --> 00:05:08.120
greater collusion between
government and corporate

00:05:08.120 --> 00:05:11.750
interests, and the rollback
of hard won advances

00:05:11.750 --> 00:05:14.920
in environmental
and social security.

00:05:14.920 --> 00:05:17.590
With Scott Pruitt reversing
environmental gains

00:05:17.590 --> 00:05:20.410
at breakneck speed,
what is at stake

00:05:20.410 --> 00:05:22.930
is nothing less than the
very idea of the greater

00:05:22.930 --> 00:05:25.020
social good.

00:05:25.020 --> 00:05:27.090
These are times that are
particularly well suited

00:05:27.090 --> 00:05:28.840
to environmental justice.

00:05:28.840 --> 00:05:33.672
A politics born out of
necessity and possibility.

00:05:33.672 --> 00:05:35.630
From the vantage point
of environmental justice

00:05:35.630 --> 00:05:39.530
communities, however, the crisis
in ecological and social health

00:05:39.530 --> 00:05:43.160
has been urgent for a
very, very long time.

00:05:43.160 --> 00:05:45.890
Capitalism-- even
the democratic kind--

00:05:45.890 --> 00:05:48.530
has always had its
sacrifice zones

00:05:48.530 --> 00:05:50.540
where ecologies and
populations have

00:05:50.540 --> 00:05:53.120
been treated as expendable.

00:05:53.120 --> 00:05:56.060
Within the United States
most of the sacrifice zones

00:05:56.060 --> 00:05:58.910
are poor and non-white,
and have been

00:05:58.910 --> 00:06:02.840
subject to repeated
histories of marginalization.

00:06:02.840 --> 00:06:05.000
The list is long--

00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:10.270
Warren County, North Carolina,
Yucca Mountain, Nevada,

00:06:10.270 --> 00:06:13.240
the Lower Ninth
Ward in New Orleans,

00:06:13.240 --> 00:06:18.530
Flint, Michigan Chicago's south
side, the Standing Rock Indian

00:06:18.530 --> 00:06:23.760
reservation, Puerto Rico,
Roxbury, Massachusetts,

00:06:23.760 --> 00:06:26.682
and on, and on, and on.

00:06:26.682 --> 00:06:29.140
These are also places where
environmental justice movements

00:06:29.140 --> 00:06:33.310
have arisen, that point to the
overlap between race, class,

00:06:33.310 --> 00:06:36.370
dispossession, and toxicity.

00:06:36.370 --> 00:06:38.170
These movements
eliminate the limits

00:06:38.170 --> 00:06:40.660
of mainstream
environmentalism, and the need

00:06:40.660 --> 00:06:44.050
to bring within its purview
industrial regulation,

00:06:44.050 --> 00:06:47.060
public health,
occupational safety, labor

00:06:47.060 --> 00:06:51.820
rights, urban green space,
and sustainable cities.

00:06:51.820 --> 00:06:53.350
In this sense,
environmental justice

00:06:53.350 --> 00:06:56.350
has always been a
universalistic politics

00:06:56.350 --> 00:07:02.149
aimed at prioritizing public
goods over private gain.

00:07:02.149 --> 00:07:04.440
Although environmental justice
was a powerful challenge

00:07:04.440 --> 00:07:08.520
to mainstream environmentalism,
environmental justice activists

00:07:08.520 --> 00:07:09.960
typically refer
to themselves not

00:07:09.960 --> 00:07:13.560
as the new environmentalists,
but as the new civil rights

00:07:13.560 --> 00:07:15.090
activists.

00:07:15.090 --> 00:07:16.620
And they do so to
place themselves

00:07:16.620 --> 00:07:19.230
within a particular
genealogy of struggle,

00:07:19.230 --> 00:07:22.320
where the rights of nonwhite
populations and the poor

00:07:22.320 --> 00:07:24.270
have been at the center.

00:07:24.270 --> 00:07:27.180
Language-- or more
specifically storytelling--

00:07:27.180 --> 00:07:29.490
has been an important tool
within environmental justice

00:07:29.490 --> 00:07:31.950
activism for naming
and illuminating

00:07:31.950 --> 00:07:35.970
injustices that have been
invisible to a wider public.

00:07:35.970 --> 00:07:38.310
Take the term
environmental racism,

00:07:38.310 --> 00:07:41.820
coined by North Carolina pastor
and community leader Benjamin

00:07:41.820 --> 00:07:46.830
Chaffetz in 1982, to describe
the siting of a toxic waste

00:07:46.830 --> 00:07:51.030
dump in predominantly black
Warren County, North Carolina.

00:07:51.030 --> 00:07:53.240
The Warren County
mobilization racialized

00:07:53.240 --> 00:07:56.640
the anti-toxics agenda,
and generated a whole host

00:07:56.640 --> 00:08:00.780
of studies on the unequal burden
of enviromental toxicity borne

00:08:00.780 --> 00:08:03.240
by US racial minorities.

00:08:03.240 --> 00:08:06.210
By naming this phenomenon
environmental racism,

00:08:06.210 --> 00:08:08.400
activists expanded the
parameters of the term

00:08:08.400 --> 00:08:11.580
environment, and made visible
a widespread experience shared

00:08:11.580 --> 00:08:15.240
by poor and nonwhite communities
across the United States.

00:08:15.240 --> 00:08:17.640
Similarly environmental
apartheid--

00:08:17.640 --> 00:08:21.390
another term coined by urban
planning scholar and activist

00:08:21.390 --> 00:08:22.740
Robert Bullard--

00:08:22.740 --> 00:08:26.430
pointed to the overlap of
race, place, and toxicity.

00:08:26.430 --> 00:08:28.700
And the parallel
hazards of black life

00:08:28.700 --> 00:08:33.370
in apartheid South Africa and
the democratic United States.

00:08:33.370 --> 00:08:34.809
Through these
practices of naming,

00:08:34.809 --> 00:08:38.200
environmental justice
disrupts normative narratives

00:08:38.200 --> 00:08:40.270
about which places
and which people

00:08:40.270 --> 00:08:43.360
have value, and shapes
alternative imaginations

00:08:43.360 --> 00:08:46.080
of place and politics.

00:08:46.080 --> 00:08:49.000
It also offers ways to
channel experiences of harm

00:08:49.000 --> 00:08:51.580
into public knowledge
and collective action

00:08:51.580 --> 00:08:53.840
at different scales.

00:08:53.840 --> 00:08:56.830
As our panelists will show
eloquently through their work,

00:08:56.830 --> 00:08:58.400
envirometal justice
is a multi-scaler

00:08:58.400 --> 00:09:02.000
of politics that ranges
from the scale of the body,

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:05.780
to that of the home, the
neighborhood, city, nation,

00:09:05.780 --> 00:09:07.456
and beyond.

00:09:07.456 --> 00:09:09.830
So what does it mean to think
about environmental justice

00:09:09.830 --> 00:09:12.910
at different scales?

00:09:12.910 --> 00:09:15.360
My justice has always
emphasized that importance

00:09:15.360 --> 00:09:19.420
of grounded experience to
transformative politics.

00:09:19.420 --> 00:09:23.130
As stated in the charter
of the 1991 National

00:09:23.130 --> 00:09:26.400
People of Color Environmental
Leadership Summit, convened

00:09:26.400 --> 00:09:29.340
in Washington DC,
enviromental justice

00:09:29.340 --> 00:09:33.150
is about doing environmental
in the very places, quote,

00:09:33.150 --> 00:09:37.600
"Where we live, work,
study, and play" unquote.

00:09:37.600 --> 00:09:39.730
The embodied
experience of locality

00:09:39.730 --> 00:09:42.730
has been key to the making
of knowledge of community

00:09:42.730 --> 00:09:44.890
and of politics.

00:09:44.890 --> 00:09:46.870
The emphasis on
the local scale has

00:09:46.870 --> 00:09:49.870
been a way to foreground the
meanings, through which people

00:09:49.870 --> 00:09:53.640
who are typically
written out of, or simply

00:09:53.640 --> 00:09:55.970
subsumed within
larger narratives,

00:09:55.970 --> 00:09:57.960
make sense of their own lives.

00:09:57.960 --> 00:09:59.730
It's an argument
for their agency

00:09:59.730 --> 00:10:01.990
in interpreting the
past, the present,

00:10:01.990 --> 00:10:04.460
and building a better future.

00:10:04.460 --> 00:10:06.740
But environmental justice
has never been just

00:10:06.740 --> 00:10:08.780
about the local scale--

00:10:08.780 --> 00:10:11.090
it's also been about the
broader contextualization

00:10:11.090 --> 00:10:14.690
of local experiences, to make
clear shared predicaments,

00:10:14.690 --> 00:10:17.240
and enable coalition building.

00:10:17.240 --> 00:10:20.240
The need to think and act
both within and across scales

00:10:20.240 --> 00:10:22.250
has only grown
with the expansion

00:10:22.250 --> 00:10:24.590
of the movement over
time from its beginnings

00:10:24.590 --> 00:10:27.480
in the citing of dirty
industries and toxic waste,

00:10:27.480 --> 00:10:29.330
to now taking on
issues as diverse

00:10:29.330 --> 00:10:34.040
as transportation justice, urban
green space, housing quality,

00:10:34.040 --> 00:10:38.030
the beauty industry,
militarism, and climate change.

00:10:38.030 --> 00:10:40.190
Each of these issues has
required new strategies

00:10:40.190 --> 00:10:42.890
and alliances, which
foreground both the promises

00:10:42.890 --> 00:10:47.360
and tensions of working in
coalitions across scales.

00:10:47.360 --> 00:10:50.600
We have very powerful
examples of such solidarity.

00:10:50.600 --> 00:10:53.480
Some have involved
collaboration between activists

00:10:53.480 --> 00:10:55.200
and scientists.

00:10:55.200 --> 00:10:57.510
Public health scientists
and women activists

00:10:57.510 --> 00:11:00.150
have together shown that
non-white women's heightened

00:11:00.150 --> 00:11:03.390
exposure to toxic chemicals
in beauty products

00:11:03.390 --> 00:11:06.660
is an instance of a
global health disparity.

00:11:06.660 --> 00:11:09.870
In doing so, they've linked the
toxins in hair straighteners,

00:11:09.870 --> 00:11:12.060
skin lighteners and
non-white women's

00:11:12.060 --> 00:11:15.550
bodies to structural racism.

00:11:15.550 --> 00:11:17.900
While toxins are one
diagnostic of broader

00:11:17.900 --> 00:11:21.369
structural conditions,
water is another.

00:11:21.369 --> 00:11:23.660
Water has been at the heart
of an environmental justice

00:11:23.660 --> 00:11:26.930
politics that is both
local and trans-local.

00:11:26.930 --> 00:11:32.600
In Gaza, Flint, Durban,
Cochabama, Bhopal, and Standing

00:11:32.600 --> 00:11:36.500
Rock, residents have demanded
the right to water as is safe,

00:11:36.500 --> 00:11:40.080
evenly distributed,
public resource.

00:11:40.080 --> 00:11:43.670
The claim to water as life
is a far-reaching critique

00:11:43.670 --> 00:11:46.790
of commodification,
privatization, and settler

00:11:46.790 --> 00:11:49.640
colonialism that has brought
residents into alliance

00:11:49.640 --> 00:11:51.770
with lawyers, litigating
on their behalf

00:11:51.770 --> 00:11:54.660
against both states and
corporate polluters.

00:11:54.660 --> 00:11:57.560
Once these similar efforts
to illuminate commonalities

00:11:57.560 --> 00:11:59.780
through shared struggles
around the right

00:11:59.780 --> 00:12:04.860
to housing, to transportation
equity, and to green space.

00:12:04.860 --> 00:12:08.500
So these are examples of how
environmental justice scales up

00:12:08.500 --> 00:12:11.530
from the most intimate and
everyday forms of bodily

00:12:11.530 --> 00:12:16.370
harm and need, to wider
systems of oppression.

00:12:16.370 --> 00:12:18.440
By contrast, the
climate justice movement

00:12:18.440 --> 00:12:20.810
works in the other direction.

00:12:20.810 --> 00:12:25.760
By reframing global warming
as an environmental injustice,

00:12:25.760 --> 00:12:28.310
the movement scales
down to highlight

00:12:28.310 --> 00:12:32.000
the localized differential
impact of climate change.

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:34.940
As a result, we now recognize
enduring differences

00:12:34.940 --> 00:12:37.970
within a shared crisis, that
most immediately affects

00:12:37.970 --> 00:12:40.670
frontline communities, such
as the victims of Hurricane

00:12:40.670 --> 00:12:44.150
Katrina, and the
Inuit of the Arctic.

00:12:44.150 --> 00:12:45.770
These and other
solidarity movements

00:12:45.770 --> 00:12:49.460
have connected the dots between
an individual health problem,

00:12:49.460 --> 00:12:51.830
or a localized
struggle for resources,

00:12:51.830 --> 00:12:55.700
and wider processes of
redlining gentrification, state

00:12:55.700 --> 00:12:58.340
violence, and corporate power.

00:12:58.340 --> 00:13:00.410
They've shown how links
between scales both

00:13:00.410 --> 00:13:05.860
perpetuate injustice, but can
also become key to battling it.

00:13:05.860 --> 00:13:08.230
And environmental justice
as a multi-scaler politics

00:13:08.230 --> 00:13:10.090
is not just about
the relationship

00:13:10.090 --> 00:13:12.650
between spatial scales.

00:13:12.650 --> 00:13:15.250
It's also about scales of time--

00:13:15.250 --> 00:13:19.300
by pointing to the birth defects
in children born 30 years

00:13:19.300 --> 00:13:22.930
after the Bhopal gas disaster,
by characterizing the water

00:13:22.930 --> 00:13:26.860
crisis in Gaza and Standing
Rock as settler colonialism,

00:13:26.860 --> 00:13:31.870
or Shell Oil's extraction sites
as petrochemical plantations,

00:13:31.870 --> 00:13:34.780
or the anthropocene
as the capitalocene,

00:13:34.780 --> 00:13:37.060
environmental justice
movements offer a different way

00:13:37.060 --> 00:13:40.090
of thinking about
and inhabiting time.

00:13:40.090 --> 00:13:43.780
Not as linear, but as
overlapping, continuous,

00:13:43.780 --> 00:13:46.390
cyclical, or repetitive.

00:13:46.390 --> 00:13:48.580
Within these conceptions
of past and present,

00:13:48.580 --> 00:13:52.895
there are also ways of
re-imagining the future.

00:13:52.895 --> 00:13:54.770
The panelists who have
joined us this evening

00:13:54.770 --> 00:13:57.410
represent a few of
the remarkable women--

00:13:57.410 --> 00:14:00.290
women of color-- working
on the front lines,

00:14:00.290 --> 00:14:04.520
and across different scales
of environmental justice.

00:14:04.520 --> 00:14:07.970
Kalila Barnett is currently
the interim director,

00:14:07.970 --> 00:14:11.270
executive director of the Dudley
Street Neighborhood Initiative,

00:14:11.270 --> 00:14:13.580
a community organization
based in the Dudley Street

00:14:13.580 --> 00:14:15.890
Neighborhood of Roxbury.

00:14:15.890 --> 00:14:18.350
Kalila is also the
former executive director

00:14:18.350 --> 00:14:21.590
of Alternatives for
Community and Environment,

00:14:21.590 --> 00:14:24.420
a leading environmental
justice organization in Boston.

00:14:24.420 --> 00:14:26.990
Kalila has over a decade
of experience in community

00:14:26.990 --> 00:14:30.560
organizing around affordable
housing, land development,

00:14:30.560 --> 00:14:32.270
and environmental justice.

00:14:32.270 --> 00:14:35.450
She serves on the board of
Mass Budget and Policy Center,

00:14:35.450 --> 00:14:37.370
the Center for
Environmental Health,

00:14:37.370 --> 00:14:39.830
and the Center for
Economic Democracy.

00:14:39.830 --> 00:14:41.480
Kalila graduated
from Bates College

00:14:41.480 --> 00:14:43.690
with a degree in American
studies and Spanish,

00:14:43.690 --> 00:14:47.760
and is a Rothbury native, and
lifelong resident of Boston.

00:14:47.760 --> 00:14:49.980
Trina Jackson is
the practice leader

00:14:49.980 --> 00:14:52.560
for community engagement
at Mission Works, where

00:14:52.560 --> 00:14:55.140
she manages the inclusion
initiative, a grant

00:14:55.140 --> 00:14:57.420
program which funds
cross-sector collaborative

00:14:57.420 --> 00:15:00.990
work for economic justice
in communities of color.

00:15:00.990 --> 00:15:03.030
Her background includes
facilitating community

00:15:03.030 --> 00:15:07.020
dialogues, and consulting on
issues of anti-oppression,

00:15:07.020 --> 00:15:10.620
civic engagement, economic
justice, racial justice,

00:15:10.620 --> 00:15:12.810
leadership development
collaboration, and community

00:15:12.810 --> 00:15:13.850
building.

00:15:13.850 --> 00:15:16.110
Trina is also a gardener,
and is originally

00:15:16.110 --> 00:15:18.720
from Louisville, Kentucky.

00:15:18.720 --> 00:15:22.890
Indira Garmendia Alfaro
is a native of Nicaragua

00:15:22.890 --> 00:15:25.470
and resident of Chelsea
who's worked as a community

00:15:25.470 --> 00:15:28.720
organizer in Nicaragua
and Central America,

00:15:28.720 --> 00:15:31.950
where she used popular
education strategies to engage

00:15:31.950 --> 00:15:34.990
and empower local communities.

00:15:34.990 --> 00:15:37.975
Here, Indira has worked to
create women-led cooperatives

00:15:37.975 --> 00:15:40.990
in East Boston, and to
envision a community land

00:15:40.990 --> 00:15:42.999
trust for Chelsea.

00:15:42.999 --> 00:15:45.040
Indira is committed and
passionate about creating

00:15:45.040 --> 00:15:47.650
systemic change to bring
about racial justice

00:15:47.650 --> 00:15:50.220
and immigrants' rights.

00:15:50.220 --> 00:15:53.800
Tenbit Mitiku is a member of
Alternatives for Community

00:15:53.800 --> 00:15:55.510
and Environment,
where she has served

00:15:55.510 --> 00:16:00.280
as a volunteer, development
intern, and now development

00:16:00.280 --> 00:16:02.470
and communications assistant.

00:16:02.470 --> 00:16:06.130
Born and raised in
Addis Ababa, Ethiopia,

00:16:06.130 --> 00:16:09.040
her background includes
community oriented education,

00:16:09.040 --> 00:16:11.920
that focused on empowering
low-income women to participate

00:16:11.920 --> 00:16:13.360
in the labor force.

00:16:13.360 --> 00:16:15.760
She's also been involved
in several projects that

00:16:15.760 --> 00:16:19.750
address issues of homelessness
in the greater Boston area.

00:16:19.750 --> 00:16:22.810
Tenbit earned a sociology
degree from Simmons College,

00:16:22.810 --> 00:16:25.090
and is currently
studying global studies

00:16:25.090 --> 00:16:28.060
and international relations
at Northeastern University.

00:16:28.060 --> 00:16:29.900
Her interests are in
economic development,

00:16:29.900 --> 00:16:33.280
environmental research,
and global health equity.

00:16:33.280 --> 00:16:36.430
And last, but not least, Ami
Zota received her master's

00:16:36.430 --> 00:16:38.320
and doctorate in
environmental health

00:16:38.320 --> 00:16:40.150
at the Harvard School
of Public Health,

00:16:40.150 --> 00:16:41.680
and is now an
assistant professor

00:16:41.680 --> 00:16:43.240
in the Department
of Environmental

00:16:43.240 --> 00:16:47.170
and Occupational Health at
George Washington University's

00:16:47.170 --> 00:16:49.420
Milken School of Public Health.

00:16:49.420 --> 00:16:51.790
Ami's work seeks to secure
environmental justice

00:16:51.790 --> 00:16:54.160
and improve health equity
through advancements

00:16:54.160 --> 00:16:57.040
in science, policy,
and clinical practice.

00:16:57.040 --> 00:16:59.140
Her research identifies
novel pathways

00:16:59.140 --> 00:17:02.560
linking social disparities,
environmental exposures,

00:17:02.560 --> 00:17:04.927
and reproductive and
children's health.

00:17:04.927 --> 00:17:06.760
Ami received a career
development grant from

00:17:06.760 --> 00:17:08.440
the National
Institutes of Health,

00:17:08.440 --> 00:17:10.990
and was recently recognized
as a pioneer under 40--

00:17:10.990 --> 00:17:13.420
she's a baby--

00:17:13.420 --> 00:17:16.320
pioneer under 40 in
environmental public health.

00:17:16.320 --> 00:17:18.819
Her research has been featured
in national and international

00:17:18.819 --> 00:17:22.150
media, and has helped shape
health and safety standards

00:17:22.150 --> 00:17:24.030
for toxic chemicals.

00:17:24.030 --> 00:17:25.510
So before turning
to our panelists,

00:17:25.510 --> 00:17:27.093
let me just say a
little about myself,

00:17:27.093 --> 00:17:29.662
and why I'm so excited
for this panel.

00:17:29.662 --> 00:17:34.030
So I'm an anthropologist, and
my work is on rights politics

00:17:34.030 --> 00:17:35.360
in India.

00:17:35.360 --> 00:17:38.020
At Harvard, I teach an
undergraduate course

00:17:38.020 --> 00:17:41.500
titled politics of nature, which
is devoted to understanding

00:17:41.500 --> 00:17:43.840
the relationship between
environmental injustice

00:17:43.840 --> 00:17:45.220
and social inequality.

00:17:45.220 --> 00:17:47.590
And each time I've
taught it, Ami and Trina

00:17:47.590 --> 00:17:49.960
have done guest lectures,
and the students

00:17:49.960 --> 00:17:53.260
have gone on a toxic
tour, organized by ACE--

00:17:53.260 --> 00:17:57.974
the organization that Tenbit
and Kalila have been a part of.

00:17:57.974 --> 00:17:59.890
And most of the students
who take the course--

00:17:59.890 --> 00:18:01.348
and some of them
are actually here,

00:18:01.348 --> 00:18:03.012
which I'm really
delighted about--

00:18:03.012 --> 00:18:04.720
most of them take the
course because they

00:18:04.720 --> 00:18:08.410
have some investment in
environmentalism of politics,

00:18:08.410 --> 00:18:10.300
and many would even
characterize themselves

00:18:10.300 --> 00:18:12.130
as environmentalists.

00:18:12.130 --> 00:18:13.690
But a lot of them
typically don't

00:18:13.690 --> 00:18:17.470
think about environmentalism
as social justice politics.

00:18:17.470 --> 00:18:21.310
And that's what the course
really pushes them to do.

00:18:21.310 --> 00:18:23.170
And this is why I
think this panel is

00:18:23.170 --> 00:18:26.770
so important as an addition
to the Mahindra Environment

00:18:26.770 --> 00:18:27.959
forum--

00:18:27.959 --> 00:18:29.500
and my hope is that
this conversation

00:18:29.500 --> 00:18:32.890
about environmental
justice, and local activism,

00:18:32.890 --> 00:18:35.260
will have a lasting
impact on how

00:18:35.260 --> 00:18:38.830
we think about the environmental
humanities [INAUDIBLE]..

00:18:38.830 --> 00:18:40.980
So let's turn now
to our panelists.

00:18:40.980 --> 00:18:44.860
I've asked each of them to
speak for about 10 minutes,

00:18:44.860 --> 00:18:47.421
after which we'll open
up the floor to Q&amp;A.

00:18:47.421 --> 00:18:48.920
So we're going to
start with Kalila.

00:18:56.490 --> 00:18:58.950
Thank you so much for the
opportunity to be here

00:18:58.950 --> 00:19:02.360
on this cold, wet afternoon.

00:19:02.360 --> 00:19:07.560
Especially, I'm happy to be here
amongst this wonderful group

00:19:07.560 --> 00:19:12.180
of panelists and women who,
some of whom I've worked with,

00:19:12.180 --> 00:19:14.100
some of whom I've
just met today.

00:19:14.100 --> 00:19:17.190
It's a real honor for me.

00:19:17.190 --> 00:19:22.200
So I was asked to speak
about the scale of the city,

00:19:22.200 --> 00:19:24.000
in terms of
environmental justice.

00:19:24.000 --> 00:19:26.460
And so I will be
talking primarily

00:19:26.460 --> 00:19:29.250
about my experience and my
work in the city of Boston,

00:19:29.250 --> 00:19:33.300
because that is the place
that I know the best,

00:19:33.300 --> 00:19:36.360
for better or for worse.

00:19:36.360 --> 00:19:42.160
And I wanted to start by
talking about this event that's

00:19:42.160 --> 00:19:43.990
coming up, that
I hope all of you

00:19:43.990 --> 00:19:49.070
will participate in, that's
very inspiring to me.

00:19:49.070 --> 00:19:53.120
So May 1st is World
Asthma Day, and it is also

00:19:53.120 --> 00:19:55.550
International Workers Day.

00:19:55.550 --> 00:19:59.960
One of the organizations that
I am very closely connected to,

00:19:59.960 --> 00:20:02.750
because of my work at
ACE, and my activism work,

00:20:02.750 --> 00:20:04.910
is Community Labor United.

00:20:04.910 --> 00:20:08.390
And that organization has formed
a coalition called the Green

00:20:08.390 --> 00:20:10.750
Justice Coalition.

00:20:10.750 --> 00:20:12.790
And it's a group
of organizations

00:20:12.790 --> 00:20:15.040
across the state of
Massachusetts, community

00:20:15.040 --> 00:20:18.310
organizations, environmental
organizations, and labor

00:20:18.310 --> 00:20:23.620
unions, who are organizing
around the intersection

00:20:23.620 --> 00:20:26.740
of environment and economics.

00:20:26.740 --> 00:20:30.520
And the event that we're
putting together that day

00:20:30.520 --> 00:20:31.990
is called #letusbreathe.

00:20:35.190 --> 00:20:37.320
And the way that we
envision this event

00:20:37.320 --> 00:20:40.300
is just by this
brief statement--

00:20:40.300 --> 00:20:44.180
"Around the world, there are
people struggling to breathe.

00:20:44.180 --> 00:20:47.180
For some, it is the
effect of pollution.

00:20:47.180 --> 00:20:52.040
For others, crippling heat,
intensified by climate change.

00:20:52.040 --> 00:20:54.710
And then there are folks
like Eric Garner, whose

00:20:54.710 --> 00:20:58.370
airways were restricted
by a combination of asthma

00:20:58.370 --> 00:21:01.640
and brutal force."

00:21:01.640 --> 00:21:04.370
And for me, this
is a real summation

00:21:04.370 --> 00:21:07.880
of where the environmental
justice movement is at,

00:21:07.880 --> 00:21:09.320
at this moment.

00:21:11.880 --> 00:21:18.090
So in many ways the shape of the
environmental justice movement,

00:21:18.090 --> 00:21:22.830
the kind of battles that
we're facing in 2018,

00:21:22.830 --> 00:21:26.190
are different than they
were when I started at ACE,

00:21:26.190 --> 00:21:30.510
and when large
environmental justice

00:21:30.510 --> 00:21:33.917
organizations across the
country were formed in the '90s.

00:21:33.917 --> 00:21:36.000
The sort of structures
that we're fighting against

00:21:36.000 --> 00:21:38.460
are still remaining,
but the battles

00:21:38.460 --> 00:21:42.380
look a little bit different.

00:21:42.380 --> 00:21:45.050
And the struggle really,
at this moment, I think,

00:21:45.050 --> 00:21:47.780
is trying to figure out how
do we build the kind of power

00:21:47.780 --> 00:21:52.370
that we need to achieve the kind
of change that we want to see.

00:21:52.370 --> 00:21:55.070
And for us, that's really
about the power and control

00:21:55.070 --> 00:21:57.530
to make decisions
about our lives,

00:21:57.530 --> 00:22:02.240
and the ways in which we want
to transform our community.

00:22:02.240 --> 00:22:04.220
And in Boston, in
particular, I think

00:22:04.220 --> 00:22:09.020
there's kind of three ways
that the landscape of how

00:22:09.020 --> 00:22:13.440
we're working has really
had to change and to adapt.

00:22:13.440 --> 00:22:18.080
I think one of the biggest
drivers is the cost of land

00:22:18.080 --> 00:22:20.280
and the cost of housing.

00:22:20.280 --> 00:22:27.720
So I grew up in Roxbury, and
during my middle school period

00:22:27.720 --> 00:22:30.850
I was bussed to a
school in the suburbs.

00:22:30.850 --> 00:22:32.880
I was a part of
the METCO program.

00:22:32.880 --> 00:22:35.250
And so at that
time period, when I

00:22:35.250 --> 00:22:37.620
would go to Wayland,
where I went to school,

00:22:37.620 --> 00:22:42.610
and tell people that I lived
in Roxbury, it was like, whoa,

00:22:42.610 --> 00:22:43.770
it's so dangerous there.

00:22:43.770 --> 00:22:46.086
I can't believe you've
even made it out here.

00:22:46.086 --> 00:22:47.910
[LAUGHS]

00:22:47.910 --> 00:22:51.100
Somehow I survived
all of those years,

00:22:51.100 --> 00:22:54.240
and was able to be
a part of a thriving

00:22:54.240 --> 00:22:55.440
and beautiful community.

00:22:55.440 --> 00:22:56.695
But that was the image.

00:22:59.390 --> 00:23:02.920
But now, many of
those people who

00:23:02.920 --> 00:23:06.310
were contemporaries
of my younger siblings

00:23:06.310 --> 00:23:08.140
are moving towards the city--

00:23:08.140 --> 00:23:13.030
are buying condos, are
starting businesses,

00:23:13.030 --> 00:23:14.800
and there's a lot of
speculation that's

00:23:14.800 --> 00:23:18.220
going on around the vacant
properties around where

00:23:18.220 --> 00:23:20.860
I grew up.

00:23:20.860 --> 00:23:23.710
Members of our
organization of ACE,

00:23:23.710 --> 00:23:27.160
other organizations that
we're closely connected to,

00:23:27.160 --> 00:23:29.020
are facing rent
increases, and are

00:23:29.020 --> 00:23:31.300
having to move
further and further

00:23:31.300 --> 00:23:35.740
outside the city of Boston,
outside of their community.

00:23:35.740 --> 00:23:38.350
Sometimes even to southeastern
parts of the state,

00:23:38.350 --> 00:23:41.482
so outside of even the
greater Boston region.

00:23:41.482 --> 00:23:43.440
And that's pretty different
from the conditions

00:23:43.440 --> 00:23:45.910
that we were facing
in the early '90s.

00:23:45.910 --> 00:23:48.840
So if you think about
organizations coming together

00:23:48.840 --> 00:23:51.570
during that time,
particularly in major cities

00:23:51.570 --> 00:23:55.800
across the country, dealing
with the impacts of--

00:23:55.800 --> 00:24:00.180
or the consequences of
redlining, of disinvestment.

00:24:00.180 --> 00:24:02.400
The organization that I'm
connected to right now,

00:24:02.400 --> 00:24:04.920
the Dudley Street
Neighborhood Initiative,

00:24:04.920 --> 00:24:07.620
was when residents came
together to get eminent domain

00:24:07.620 --> 00:24:10.020
powers to take back
control of the land.

00:24:12.610 --> 00:24:16.240
The other thing that has also
very much changed, I would say,

00:24:16.240 --> 00:24:18.410
is the wealth gap
that we're facing.

00:24:18.410 --> 00:24:22.780
So there's always been a huge
disparity, always been troubles

00:24:22.780 --> 00:24:24.520
and challenges with that.

00:24:24.520 --> 00:24:27.820
But a recent study that
was done in 2016, called

00:24:27.820 --> 00:24:30.880
the Color of Wealth, mentions
that white households

00:24:30.880 --> 00:24:34.060
in the Boston area had the
median net worth of a quarter

00:24:34.060 --> 00:24:37.720
of a million dollars,
while black households have

00:24:37.720 --> 00:24:40.480
a net worth of $8--

00:24:40.480 --> 00:24:43.200
$8.

00:24:43.200 --> 00:24:47.760
So not only are residents
facing pressures

00:24:47.760 --> 00:24:50.730
from a speculative land
and housing market,

00:24:50.730 --> 00:24:54.330
they are not able
to find the wealth,

00:24:54.330 --> 00:24:56.640
they're not able
to find the income

00:24:56.640 --> 00:24:59.760
to bring themselves into place.

00:24:59.760 --> 00:25:02.280
And then the third piece I
think is really important

00:25:02.280 --> 00:25:06.600
is the actual infrastructure of
grassroots community organizing

00:25:06.600 --> 00:25:09.900
entities across our region.

00:25:09.900 --> 00:25:15.090
So while I was at ACE,
my job was fundraising,

00:25:15.090 --> 00:25:19.800
was asking for resources to
help us build out the organizing

00:25:19.800 --> 00:25:23.280
work that we needed to
do to build leadership

00:25:23.280 --> 00:25:24.840
within our communities.

00:25:24.840 --> 00:25:26.850
And even during the
course of my eight years

00:25:26.850 --> 00:25:30.270
there, we saw a number
of national foundations

00:25:30.270 --> 00:25:33.780
who moved away from funding
grassroots organizing.

00:25:33.780 --> 00:25:38.010
A lot of money shifted towards
a national climate bill--

00:25:38.010 --> 00:25:40.980
a lot of money given to large
environmental organizations,

00:25:40.980 --> 00:25:43.260
and not given to us.

00:25:43.260 --> 00:25:45.630
And so the infrastructure
upon which we really

00:25:45.630 --> 00:25:49.200
need to build our movements
has gotten more fragile,

00:25:49.200 --> 00:25:50.770
I would say, over time.

00:25:50.770 --> 00:25:53.130
And that's really something
important to consider

00:25:53.130 --> 00:25:53.880
and to talk about.

00:25:56.670 --> 00:26:03.780
But I want to end on
a more positive note.

00:26:03.780 --> 00:26:06.810
And to offer a couple of
thoughts about, even given

00:26:06.810 --> 00:26:09.150
those conditions, how do we
build the kind of movement

00:26:09.150 --> 00:26:09.780
that we need?

00:26:09.780 --> 00:26:13.710
How do we build more
events, more collaborations,

00:26:13.710 --> 00:26:17.050
like #letusbreathe?

00:26:17.050 --> 00:26:19.570
So one thing I think
is, we need to have

00:26:19.570 --> 00:26:22.030
a bold and audacious
vision that goes

00:26:22.030 --> 00:26:25.150
across a bunch of
different boundaries.

00:26:25.150 --> 00:26:28.360
We need to not be
afraid to ask for

00:26:28.360 --> 00:26:30.850
and to demand the
kind of resources

00:26:30.850 --> 00:26:32.800
that our communities
really need,

00:26:32.800 --> 00:26:35.350
rather than just what we
think is politically feasible.

00:26:38.890 --> 00:26:41.710
One of the ways in which
we're beginning to do that

00:26:41.710 --> 00:26:45.100
is by building what we're
calling a 10-year agenda.

00:26:45.100 --> 00:26:49.420
So it is an opportunity
for organizations

00:26:49.420 --> 00:26:51.970
across different
sectors to come together

00:26:51.970 --> 00:26:54.610
and to say, what do we want
the state of Massachusetts

00:26:54.610 --> 00:26:57.490
to look like over the
course of the next 10 years?

00:26:57.490 --> 00:26:59.470
And we're thinking
not just about,

00:26:59.470 --> 00:27:01.120
what does it look
like in education?

00:27:01.120 --> 00:27:02.380
What does it look
like in housing?

00:27:02.380 --> 00:27:03.820
But what does it
actually look like when

00:27:03.820 --> 00:27:06.089
we think about those things
in an intersectional way,

00:27:06.089 --> 00:27:07.255
and really do them together?

00:27:09.790 --> 00:27:14.140
I think we're also talking about
this idea of a just transition.

00:27:14.140 --> 00:27:17.200
So we know, because the
climate is changing,

00:27:17.200 --> 00:27:19.240
that things are
going to keep moving.

00:27:19.240 --> 00:27:22.390
The change is inevitable,
but justice is not inevitable

00:27:22.390 --> 00:27:26.690
unless we speak out, unless
we make a difference.

00:27:26.690 --> 00:27:28.750
And so using this idea
of just transition,

00:27:28.750 --> 00:27:32.620
we're fueling experiments and
projects that would actually

00:27:32.620 --> 00:27:35.350
have community members
make decisions,

00:27:35.350 --> 00:27:37.420
and govern, and lead.

00:27:37.420 --> 00:27:41.110
One of them is a micro-grid
project that folks in Chelsea

00:27:41.110 --> 00:27:43.510
are working on,
and also Chinatown

00:27:43.510 --> 00:27:48.130
within the city of Boston, where
there is a micro-grid that's

00:27:48.130 --> 00:27:50.110
owned by the community.

00:27:50.110 --> 00:27:54.490
So if there is ever a
major weather event,

00:27:54.490 --> 00:27:57.250
we know what the impacts can be
when people don't have access

00:27:57.250 --> 00:28:01.040
to the resources they need,
electricity, water, et cetera.

00:28:01.040 --> 00:28:03.730
So how do we prepare
ourselves for those things

00:28:03.730 --> 00:28:06.220
that we know that
are coming, but do so

00:28:06.220 --> 00:28:08.200
in a way that shifts
the ownership?

00:28:08.200 --> 00:28:09.820
Shifts who gets
to make decisions

00:28:09.820 --> 00:28:11.470
about those
resources, and really

00:28:11.470 --> 00:28:16.220
begin to make those
decisions together?

00:28:16.220 --> 00:28:18.350
I think, in closing,
the other things that

00:28:18.350 --> 00:28:21.320
give me hope and signal
to the kind of movement

00:28:21.320 --> 00:28:24.980
that we need to be building is
the rise of the climate justice

00:28:24.980 --> 00:28:25.710
movement.

