00:32:01.330 --> 00:32:03.370
my college education.

00:32:03.370 --> 00:32:07.010
And so have this interest
in African-American women

00:32:07.010 --> 00:32:10.340
and our gardening practices.

00:32:10.340 --> 00:32:14.570
And I thought for a long
time, what language am I

00:32:14.570 --> 00:32:16.720
going to give this interest?

00:32:16.720 --> 00:32:19.910
What is the story that
I'm really trying to tell?

00:32:19.910 --> 00:32:23.520
And so I came up with
this, Grown by Herself.

00:32:23.520 --> 00:32:27.670
Let me say a little bit
about what that means to me.

00:32:27.670 --> 00:32:32.340
The first thing is that,
gardens are stories,

00:32:32.340 --> 00:32:36.900
and they are a way that we
author and we tell our stories.

00:32:36.900 --> 00:32:41.090
And so I thought, well, how
can I make that connection?

00:32:41.090 --> 00:32:44.940
And so, Grown by Herself--

00:32:44.940 --> 00:32:50.962
so in the tradition of the
slave narratives, and that

00:32:50.962 --> 00:32:53.442
they were written
by him or herselv.

00:32:53.442 --> 00:32:56.914
These were stories
that formerly enslaved

00:32:56.914 --> 00:33:00.386
people would tell
others about what

00:33:00.386 --> 00:33:02.500
it was like to be
enslaved, because we know

00:33:02.500 --> 00:33:06.084
a lot of enslaved people did
not learn to read and write,

00:33:06.084 --> 00:33:08.000
because that was forbidden.

00:33:08.000 --> 00:33:10.440
So in order to
capture those stories,

00:33:10.440 --> 00:33:14.048
they would tell their stories
to other writers, and other

00:33:14.048 --> 00:33:15.900
[INAUDIBLE].

00:33:15.900 --> 00:33:20.460
So I took the term,
thinking that gardens

00:33:20.460 --> 00:33:24.980
are a way of authoring our
stories, Grown by Herself

00:33:24.980 --> 00:33:28.090
is very much in that
same tradition--

00:33:28.090 --> 00:33:33.100
that black women have authored
an account of their lives

00:33:33.100 --> 00:33:35.080
through gardening.

00:33:35.080 --> 00:33:38.290
And that's what the term,
Grown by Herself means.

00:33:38.290 --> 00:33:42.210
It also means about black
women have ushered and fostered

00:33:42.210 --> 00:33:44.320
environmental movements.

00:33:44.320 --> 00:33:47.200
So the environmental movement,
environmental justice,

00:33:47.200 --> 00:33:50.310
has been grown by
African-American women's garden

00:33:50.310 --> 00:33:51.807
practices.

00:33:51.807 --> 00:33:53.803
I'm just going to grab my water.

00:33:59.292 --> 00:34:02.210
So, Grown by Herself,
as I say here,

00:34:02.210 --> 00:34:05.750
is about the role
of community gardens

00:34:05.750 --> 00:34:07.680
in the lives of
African-American women

00:34:07.680 --> 00:34:10.130
in their environmental activism.

00:34:10.130 --> 00:34:11.750
And African-American
women have been

00:34:11.750 --> 00:34:13.429
at the forefront
of the leadership

00:34:13.429 --> 00:34:15.410
for environmental
justice in the US.

00:34:18.070 --> 00:34:21.020
Their activism has been
about mobilizing communities

00:34:21.020 --> 00:34:25.100
to shut down power plants
in their neighborhoods,

00:34:25.100 --> 00:34:30.630
or work to beautify streets,
or to convert vacant lots Into

00:34:30.630 --> 00:34:31.380
community gardens.

00:34:31.380 --> 00:34:33.860
And those are just
a few examples

00:34:33.860 --> 00:34:35.940
of how African-American
women have

00:34:35.940 --> 00:34:41.010
led an environmental movement
in our garden practices.

00:34:41.010 --> 00:34:44.079
So let me say a
little bit about--

00:34:44.079 --> 00:34:46.400
oh, here we go--

00:34:46.400 --> 00:34:51.110
so part of my research,
for Grown by Herself,

00:34:51.110 --> 00:34:55.520
was thinking about the roots
of African-American women's

00:34:55.520 --> 00:34:58.490
gardens, and what we
grow in our gardens,

00:34:58.490 --> 00:35:02.510
and how we developed our
gardening practices over time.

00:35:02.510 --> 00:35:04.180
And so I did a little
bit of research,

00:35:04.180 --> 00:35:06.850
and I learned a lot about
the provision gardens

00:35:06.850 --> 00:35:10.690
that enslaved
people had, as part

00:35:10.690 --> 00:35:12.810
of how they would grow food.

00:35:12.810 --> 00:35:14.760
So they would work
in the fields,

00:35:14.760 --> 00:35:17.620
or they'd work in the house,
but also enslaved people

00:35:17.620 --> 00:35:20.870
had their own gardens.

00:35:20.870 --> 00:35:24.340
And of course, that
varied by situation,

00:35:24.340 --> 00:35:27.740
but in this illustration here,
that was part of my research,

00:35:27.740 --> 00:35:32.190
you see what that looked like,
and what the structure of that

00:35:32.190 --> 00:35:32.690
is.

00:35:32.690 --> 00:35:36.400
So you see the dwelling, you
see the small plots of gardens,

00:35:36.400 --> 00:35:38.750
and then you see the women
there tending their gardens.

00:35:38.750 --> 00:35:42.670
And usually, it
was the women who

00:35:42.670 --> 00:35:45.130
were doing a lot of the
tending of the gardens,

00:35:45.130 --> 00:35:47.050
and so forth and so on.

00:35:47.050 --> 00:35:51.190
And so there was a lot of
like community connection.

00:35:51.190 --> 00:35:52.990
Often different
families would come

00:35:52.990 --> 00:35:56.870
and they would plant together,
they'd grow together.

00:35:56.870 --> 00:35:59.530
And so there was a lot
of relationship-building

00:35:59.530 --> 00:36:02.180
and connection between
enslaved families.

00:36:02.180 --> 00:36:04.730
So that's just kind
of an illustration

00:36:04.730 --> 00:36:07.466
that I found as
part of my research.

00:36:13.260 --> 00:36:16.770
So I also wanted to
talk about the foods

00:36:16.770 --> 00:36:19.234
that African-American women
grew in their gardens.

00:36:19.234 --> 00:36:24.195
And I did a little bit of
research on some of the--

00:36:26.820 --> 00:36:28.320
there were lots of
different stories

00:36:28.320 --> 00:36:33.360
about how these
seeds are the foods

00:36:33.360 --> 00:36:37.530
that enslaved
African-American women grew,

00:36:37.530 --> 00:36:39.960
and how they actually made
it and survived the Middle

00:36:39.960 --> 00:36:40.530
Passage.

00:36:40.530 --> 00:36:45.850
So there's all of these stories,
which I have not really--

00:36:45.850 --> 00:36:47.390
I haven't learned
a whole lot about

00:36:47.390 --> 00:36:49.056
and found a lot of
evidence, but there's

00:36:49.056 --> 00:36:52.200
a lot of anecdotal
evidence about women hiding

00:36:52.200 --> 00:36:57.210
seeds in their hair, or lots
of different ways that some

00:36:57.210 --> 00:37:00.150
of the seeds of
these vegetables--

00:37:00.150 --> 00:37:03.990
yams, and collard greens,
and so forth and so on,

00:37:03.990 --> 00:37:06.840
food staples that are part
of the African-American diet

00:37:06.840 --> 00:37:09.750
were actually grown
in these gardens.

00:37:09.750 --> 00:37:12.120
That was also just part
of my own learning.

00:37:15.380 --> 00:37:18.690
And what these practices
really meant to me

00:37:18.690 --> 00:37:24.130
was that women were--

00:37:24.130 --> 00:37:27.970
they had a resilience, that
even in those conditions

00:37:27.970 --> 00:37:30.880
of enslavement,
African-American women

00:37:30.880 --> 00:37:36.670
were committed to a community
story and identity that

00:37:36.670 --> 00:37:40.520
was more about
self-determination,

00:37:40.520 --> 00:37:44.670
which has been a constant theme
of environmental justice work.

00:37:44.670 --> 00:37:49.210
So that theme continues to
be the way that we think

00:37:49.210 --> 00:37:50.580
about environmental justice--

00:37:50.580 --> 00:37:54.760
as people directly impacted,
telling their own stories,

00:37:54.760 --> 00:37:56.647
being very self-determinant.

00:38:01.540 --> 00:38:08.280
So I was also interested
in, at the end of slavery,

00:38:08.280 --> 00:38:13.340
how did African-American
women continue the gardening

00:38:13.340 --> 00:38:18.930
practices, especially for
people that stayed in the South.

00:38:18.930 --> 00:38:22.430
And so this picture here
is just a reflection

00:38:22.430 --> 00:38:26.790
of how a lot of the
foods that people grew,

00:38:26.790 --> 00:38:29.500
they continue to grow, if
they were able to hold on

00:38:29.500 --> 00:38:32.900
to land in the South.

00:38:32.900 --> 00:38:38.450
And this is just a
reflection of even the way

00:38:38.450 --> 00:38:42.630
that people grow food in
rows, and so forth and so on.

00:38:42.630 --> 00:38:44.600
And how it just
continues to be a way

00:38:44.600 --> 00:38:50.060
that African-American women
continue to take leadership

00:38:50.060 --> 00:38:53.720
just around connection to land,
family connection to land,

00:38:53.720 --> 00:38:55.726
family connection to tradition.

00:39:04.300 --> 00:39:10.780
So also, I was thinking, then,
how this evolved over time,

00:39:10.780 --> 00:39:14.440
into the vacant
lot gardening that

00:39:14.440 --> 00:39:18.580
became kind of the hallmark
of the civil rights movement.

00:39:18.580 --> 00:39:21.420
And the growth of the
environmental justice movement

00:39:21.420 --> 00:39:25.210
with the toxic waste
study in the late '80s,

00:39:25.210 --> 00:39:30.730
in the early '70s, when
black families were really

00:39:30.730 --> 00:39:37.330
starting to want to be very
self-determinant about what

00:39:37.330 --> 00:39:39.310
was happening in
their neighborhoods,

00:39:39.310 --> 00:39:43.570
and the disinvestment
in black neighborhoods,

00:39:43.570 --> 00:39:50.530
and the open lots that city
governments didn't really

00:39:50.530 --> 00:39:51.080
take care of.

00:39:51.080 --> 00:39:55.120
So families would,
and communities

00:39:55.120 --> 00:39:58.450
would start to do
a lot of activism

00:39:58.450 --> 00:40:00.640
around the vacant lots.

00:40:00.640 --> 00:40:03.580
And so it just became--

00:40:03.580 --> 00:40:06.830
it's how how this form
of activism evolved,

00:40:06.830 --> 00:40:09.860
and African-American were
at the forefront of that.

00:40:17.340 --> 00:40:20.270
So again, this is
just one reflection

00:40:20.270 --> 00:40:23.390
of how this has been--

00:40:23.390 --> 00:40:26.450
young people have
been involved, and how

00:40:26.450 --> 00:40:28.754
they've learned through
these kind of practices

00:40:28.754 --> 00:40:30.170
and traditions
about what it means

00:40:30.170 --> 00:40:33.118
to be environmental leaders
in their own neighborhoods.

00:40:38.450 --> 00:40:42.100
