[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:46:10.220 --> 00:46:14.990
70% to 80% of the oil that is
used for heat in New England

00:46:14.990 --> 00:46:18.800
is also stored along
the river in Chelsea.

00:46:18.800 --> 00:46:29.690
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:46:29.690 --> 00:46:33.570
In Chelsea, we also have
more than 400,000 tons

00:46:33.570 --> 00:46:38.590
of road salt that is used for
more than 350 cities in New

00:46:38.590 --> 00:46:39.670
England.

00:46:39.670 --> 00:46:56.170
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:46:56.170 --> 00:47:01.120
Also in Chelsea, we have the
second largest produce center

00:47:01.120 --> 00:47:04.200
in the United States,
which not only serves

00:47:04.200 --> 00:47:06.430
cities in New England,
but also in other parts

00:47:06.430 --> 00:47:07.660
of the United States.

00:47:10.920 --> 00:47:15.710
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:47:15.710 --> 00:47:18.980
So now I would like to talk
about who lives in Chelsea.

00:47:18.980 --> 00:47:24.740
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:47:24.740 --> 00:47:27.170
And then we will understand
why all of these industries

00:47:27.170 --> 00:47:28.730
are found in Chelsea.

00:47:28.730 --> 00:47:37.310
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:47:37.310 --> 00:47:39.410
Out of all of the people
that live in Chelsea,

00:47:39.410 --> 00:47:42.750
73% are ethnic minorities--

00:47:42.750 --> 00:47:45.480
people that we consider
people of color.

00:47:45.480 --> 00:47:49.580
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:47:49.580 --> 00:47:52.970
24% live below the poverty line.

00:47:52.970 --> 00:48:02.930
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:48:02.930 --> 00:48:07.640
Out of those 73% of people
of color, 65% of those

00:48:07.640 --> 00:48:09.810
are immigrants, are Latinos.

00:48:09.810 --> 00:48:16.430
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:48:16.430 --> 00:48:19.850
In Chelsea, we have the highest
rates of hospitalization

00:48:19.850 --> 00:48:22.080
because of asthma.

00:48:22.080 --> 00:48:25.050
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:48:25.050 --> 00:48:26.880
We also work in East Boston.

00:48:26.880 --> 00:48:41.760
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:48:41.760 --> 00:48:46.260
East Boston, although
it's five squared miles,

00:48:46.260 --> 00:48:49.980
the people of East Boston
only live on two square miles,

00:48:49.980 --> 00:48:52.350
and that's because the
other three are used up

00:48:52.350 --> 00:48:54.550
by the airport.

00:48:54.550 --> 00:49:01.350
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:49:01.350 --> 00:49:05.220
53% of the residents
are Latino, and 17%

00:49:05.220 --> 00:49:07.144
live below the poverty line.

00:49:14.860 --> 00:49:20.204
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:49:20.204 --> 00:49:21.870
So as you can see,
we have a lot of work

00:49:21.870 --> 00:49:24.530
to do in Chelsea
and East Boston.

00:49:24.530 --> 00:49:40.340
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:49:40.340 --> 00:49:42.300
You know, in GreenRoots,
we work a lot

00:49:42.300 --> 00:49:46.170
for environmental justice, and
we have a lot of work to do,

00:49:46.170 --> 00:49:49.410
a lot of illnesses to
confront, and things

00:49:49.410 --> 00:49:53.270
that we have to solve because
they're impacting our bodies.

00:49:53.270 --> 00:50:06.930
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:50:06.930 --> 00:50:11.400
So we're trying to achieve
this environmental justice,

00:50:11.400 --> 00:50:15.030
and improve the quality of
life through collective action,

00:50:15.030 --> 00:50:18.150
unity, education,
and youth leadership

00:50:18.150 --> 00:50:20.350
in our neighborhoods
and communities.

00:50:20.350 --> 00:50:35.790
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:50:35.790 --> 00:50:38.820
These are some of the
topics that we deal with.

00:50:38.820 --> 00:50:43.290
As you can see, land and
food justice, youth power,

00:50:43.290 --> 00:50:46.740
waterfront access, energy
democracy, transit justice,

00:50:46.740 --> 00:50:50.160
clean air and public
health, and climate justice.

00:50:50.160 --> 00:50:59.210
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:51:04.560 --> 00:51:07.170
And for us, it's not
that we're trying

00:51:07.170 --> 00:51:09.990
to work for the community,
but rather with the community.

00:51:09.990 --> 00:51:12.720
Because we cannot achieve
anything that we want

00:51:12.720 --> 00:51:15.520
to achieve without working
with the community.

00:51:15.520 --> 00:51:18.750
And that's why we talk about
implementing, empowering,

00:51:18.750 --> 00:51:20.638
and engaging the community.

00:51:27.820 --> 00:51:42.120
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:51:42.120 --> 00:51:45.330
We have been working in
Chelsea for 23 years,

00:51:45.330 --> 00:51:47.670
and we have had
lots of victories.

00:51:47.670 --> 00:51:49.172
And we've also had
lots of losses.

00:51:49.172 --> 00:51:50.880
But I would like to
talk to you about one

00:51:50.880 --> 00:51:53.241
victory in particular.

00:51:53.241 --> 00:51:59.400
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:51:59.900 --> 00:52:03.670
How many of you have heard of
the power company, Cape Wind?

00:52:03.670 --> 00:52:30.050
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:52:30.050 --> 00:52:34.520
This power company,
Cape Wind, in 2006,

00:52:34.520 --> 00:52:37.970
at the same time that it
was proposing a wind power

00:52:37.970 --> 00:52:44.120
plant in Cape Cod, it was also
proposing an electrical plant

00:52:44.120 --> 00:52:46.520
to be situated right
across the street

00:52:46.520 --> 00:52:51.450
from the only elementary
school in Chelsea.

00:52:51.450 --> 00:52:52.830
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:52:52.830 --> 00:52:53.820
So why?

00:52:53.820 --> 00:52:55.650
What was the difference?

00:52:55.650 --> 00:52:57.420
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:52:57.420 --> 00:52:59.860
So just remember who
lives in Chelsea.

00:52:59.860 --> 00:53:01.050
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:53:01.050 --> 00:53:04.430
And who live in Cape Cod.

00:53:04.430 --> 00:53:16.950
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:53:16.950 --> 00:53:21.150
And in 2006, we were able
to beat the company--

00:53:21.150 --> 00:53:23.370
we were able to
beat this proposal,

00:53:23.370 --> 00:53:25.420
so that it wasn't built
right across the street.

00:53:25.420 --> 00:53:31.680
This is just an idea of what
the electrical plant would

00:53:31.680 --> 00:53:33.750
have looked like if it
had been constructed

00:53:33.750 --> 00:53:36.750
right across the street
from the elementary school.

00:53:36.750 --> 00:53:50.130
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:53:50.130 --> 00:53:52.290
We were able to
stop this project

00:53:52.290 --> 00:53:56.310
with public action, oral
and written testimonies,

00:53:56.310 --> 00:53:59.190
collecting signatures from
the residents of the city,

00:53:59.190 --> 00:54:01.140
and legal advocacy.

00:54:01.140 --> 00:54:03.070
And we were fighting
for a year and a half,

00:54:03.070 --> 00:54:06.168
but we were finally able to win.

00:54:06.168 --> 00:54:07.596
[APPLAUSE]

00:54:11.880 --> 00:54:21.280
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:54:21.280 --> 00:54:23.450
We're doing a lot of
different projects,

00:54:23.450 --> 00:54:25.640
we have a lot of
work, as you can see--

00:54:25.640 --> 00:54:28.430
there's a lot of work to
be done in these areas.

00:54:28.430 --> 00:54:30.992
But I want to share
two particular projects

00:54:30.992 --> 00:54:31.700
that we're doing.

00:54:34.424 --> 00:54:47.390
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:54:47.390 --> 00:54:50.300
We're working on a
micro-grid, in collaboration

00:54:50.300 --> 00:54:53.660
with the organization
Green Justice Coalition.

00:54:53.660 --> 00:54:57.050
We won $75,000 to
conduct a study

00:54:57.050 --> 00:55:00.780
on micro-grids in Chelsea.

00:55:00.780 --> 00:55:10.050
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:55:10.050 --> 00:55:12.510
This micro-grid
would be connected

00:55:12.510 --> 00:55:17.940
to the much larger energy grid
of the electrical company.

00:55:17.940 --> 00:55:19.075
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:55:28.540 --> 00:55:31.530
It's a little bit complicated
to explain it, but--

00:55:31.530 --> 00:55:32.700
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:55:32.700 --> 00:55:34.490
But I'm going to try.

00:55:34.490 --> 00:55:42.410
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:55:42.410 --> 00:55:48.700
So the buildings that would
be connected to the grid

00:55:48.700 --> 00:55:52.510
would produce their own
renewable energy, whether solar

00:55:52.510 --> 00:55:54.500
or wind.

00:55:54.500 --> 00:55:58.170
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:55:58.170 --> 00:56:01.350
And then they could sell this
energy to the larger company.

00:56:01.350 --> 00:56:04.440
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:56:04.440 --> 00:56:07.660
And in that way,
reduce energy costs.

00:56:07.660 --> 00:56:27.210
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:56:27.210 --> 00:56:28.680
These buildings,
the buildings that

00:56:28.680 --> 00:56:30.750
would be connected
to the micro-grid,

00:56:30.750 --> 00:56:35.610
would be public schools,
municipal buildings, hospitals,

00:56:35.610 --> 00:56:39.480
public housing, and the
large produce market

00:56:39.480 --> 00:56:43.000
that I was mentioning earlier
that serves many communities,

00:56:43.000 --> 00:56:44.930
in addition to New England.

00:56:44.930 --> 00:56:46.080
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:56:48.720 --> 00:56:55.680
So we are looking beyond
our local borders.

00:56:55.680 --> 00:57:02.000
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:57:02.500 --> 00:57:04.780
Also, if there's a
natural disaster,

00:57:04.780 --> 00:57:06.820
the residents of
the town could go

00:57:06.820 --> 00:57:11.830
to these buildings as shelter.

00:57:11.830 --> 00:57:16.380
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:57:16.380 --> 00:57:20.152
And this would also prevent
what our brothers in Puerto Rico

00:57:20.152 --> 00:57:20.735
have suffered.

00:57:25.380 --> 00:57:37.720
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:57:38.320 --> 00:57:41.800
Also at GreenRoots, we're
working on community land

00:57:41.800 --> 00:57:44.230
trusts, to create
these land trust

00:57:44.230 --> 00:57:47.400
with a group of immigrant
women, some Latinas who

00:57:47.400 --> 00:57:49.840
will live in Chelsea.

00:57:49.840 --> 00:57:51.110
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:58:00.790 --> 00:58:03.730
The idea actually
came from the crisis

00:58:03.730 --> 00:58:05.260
that Chelsea is
going through, and I

00:58:05.260 --> 00:58:09.460
would go as far as to say that
this is a national crisis.

00:58:09.460 --> 00:58:11.710
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:58:14.080 --> 00:58:17.110
And it's especially
an important housing

00:58:17.110 --> 00:58:22.100
crisis for people of color,
and people of low income.

00:58:22.100 --> 00:58:23.800
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:58:28.240 --> 00:58:32.230
More than 70% of the residents
in Chelsea are tenants.

00:58:32.230 --> 00:58:42.160
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:58:42.160 --> 00:58:44.950
So there's this great
crisis in Chelsea,

00:58:44.950 --> 00:58:47.650
because now that it's
being gentrified,

00:58:47.650 --> 00:58:50.770
people are seeing
their rents go up

00:58:50.770 --> 00:58:54.660
and they have to be displaced
to other communities.

00:58:54.660 --> 00:58:55.810
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:59:06.870 --> 00:59:13.140
The people in that community
understand what's going on,

00:59:13.140 --> 00:59:14.190
and the crisis--

00:59:14.190 --> 00:59:16.300
the housing crisis that
they're going through.

00:59:16.300 --> 00:59:17.850
But they also
understand that they're

00:59:17.850 --> 00:59:20.605
fighting for land
and for housing,

00:59:20.605 --> 00:59:21.980
because it's one
of their rights.

00:59:24.030 --> 00:59:25.740
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:59:33.870 --> 00:59:37.110
So in addition to
these land trusts,

00:59:37.110 --> 00:59:41.730
we also want land, in order
to build housing, community

00:59:41.730 --> 00:59:44.970
gardens, and green spaces.

00:59:44.970 --> 00:59:45.950
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:59:45.950 --> 00:59:47.420
Thank you.

00:59:47.420 --> 00:59:48.890
[APPLAUSE]

01:00:01.170 --> 01:00:06.590
So, I am from an environmental
justice organization

01:00:06.590 --> 01:00:09.800
that many of my
sisters mentioned--

01:00:09.800 --> 01:00:12.500
Alternatives for
Community and Environment,

01:00:12.500 --> 01:00:17.830
ACE, located in the
Roxbury neighborhood.

01:00:17.830 --> 01:00:21.400
For 25 years, ACE
has brought together

01:00:21.400 --> 01:00:25.030
families and communities
to build their power,

01:00:25.030 --> 01:00:28.130
to eradicate
environmental racism,

01:00:28.130 --> 01:00:32.620
classism, and create healthy
sustainable communities,

01:00:32.620 --> 01:00:35.810
and achieve
environmental justice.

01:00:35.810 --> 01:00:39.350
This mission is implemented
through a community organizing

01:00:39.350 --> 01:00:44.900
membership model that engages
and empowers people of color,

01:00:44.900 --> 01:00:48.500
and low-income communities,
to identify solutions

01:00:48.500 --> 01:00:53.660
to their shared problems, and
to run successful campaigns

01:00:53.660 --> 01:00:56.800
in implementing the solutions.

01:00:56.800 --> 01:01:01.340
That process is facilitated
through our programs.

01:01:01.340 --> 01:01:04.510
The Roxbury environmental
Empowerment Project,

01:01:04.510 --> 01:01:13.060
REAP, the T Riders Union, TRU,
the Roxbury campaign committee,

01:01:13.060 --> 01:01:16.570
our membership program,
environmental justice

01:01:16.570 --> 01:01:21.190
legal services, and our
leadership in coalitions,

01:01:21.190 --> 01:01:27.010
advancing environmental justice
in Boston and in our state.

01:01:27.010 --> 01:01:30.190
Our GreenRoots
leadership development

01:01:30.190 --> 01:01:34.000
is grounded in a
strongly held belief

01:01:34.000 --> 01:01:37.740
that those most
impacted by injustice

01:01:37.740 --> 01:01:44.200
must lead us in resisting it,
and in creating solutions.

01:01:44.200 --> 01:01:48.600
To ensure we live this belief,
and are led by members,

01:01:48.600 --> 01:01:52.360
ACE provides formal
and informal pathways

01:01:52.360 --> 01:01:57.220
for skills building, learning,
and practice within all

01:01:57.220 --> 01:02:00.810
our organizing and programs.

01:02:00.810 --> 01:02:04.440
I'd also like to mention that
women in our organization

01:02:04.440 --> 01:02:08.400
are at the core of the
environmental justice work.

01:02:08.400 --> 01:02:11.670
It is an anchor for the
movement to generate

01:02:11.670 --> 01:02:16.630
smart ideas in this struggle.

01:02:16.630 --> 01:02:18.330
Women of color at
ACE are involved

01:02:18.330 --> 01:02:21.450
in many aspects of
the administration,

01:02:21.450 --> 01:02:25.850
fundraising, and
organizing projects.

01:02:25.850 --> 01:02:31.280
I think there is also a sense
of acknowledgment in the Roxbury

01:02:31.280 --> 01:02:35.990
neighborhood, that women are at
the center of leading the youth

01:02:35.990 --> 01:02:40.790
development, that also encourage
the community to participate

01:02:40.790 --> 01:02:44.840
in urban gardening,
transportation, and health

01:02:44.840 --> 01:02:47.610
equity.

01:02:47.610 --> 01:02:51.930
We also believe in advancing
ourselves with education,

01:02:51.930 --> 01:02:55.290
so that we have all the
necessary tools to plan

01:02:55.290 --> 01:02:59.730
the next steps in our
sustainable work for better

01:02:59.730 --> 01:03:01.025
transparent policies.

01:03:04.210 --> 01:03:07.630
Our T Riders Union
program organizes

01:03:07.630 --> 01:03:10.450
transit riders from
low-income communities,

01:03:10.450 --> 01:03:14.290
and communities of color, to
advocate for better service

01:03:14.290 --> 01:03:16.690
from the MBTA.

01:03:16.690 --> 01:03:19.390
In our public
transit justice work,

01:03:19.390 --> 01:03:24.220
we also continue to collaborate
with GreenRoots Chelsea,

01:03:24.220 --> 01:03:28.930
with whom we partnered to
gain former governor Patrick's

01:03:28.930 --> 01:03:33.730
support for executive order
552, the MBTA's adoption

01:03:33.730 --> 01:03:36.116
of the youth pass program.

01:03:36.116 --> 01:03:39.200
The transportation
for Massachusetts,

01:03:39.200 --> 01:03:43.430
a diverse coalition of
over 70 partner and member

01:03:43.430 --> 01:03:48.350
organizations, who advocate
for transportation funds

01:03:48.350 --> 01:03:53.780
to be spent fairly and wisely
for transportation decisions

01:03:53.780 --> 01:03:56.900
that are transparent,
accountable,

01:03:56.900 --> 01:03:59.300
and to ensure that
our transportation

01:03:59.300 --> 01:04:03.100
system has sufficient resources
to meet the Commonwealth's

01:04:03.100 --> 01:04:03.600
needs.

01:04:06.450 --> 01:04:09.910
Roxbury Environmental
Empowerment Project--

01:04:09.910 --> 01:04:14.710
REAP-- works with youth
of color on a variety

01:04:14.710 --> 01:04:19.390
of environmental justice
issues, identified by youth

01:04:19.390 --> 01:04:22.280
as relevant to their lives.

01:04:22.280 --> 01:04:25.730
They know that a healthy
and sustainable community

01:04:25.730 --> 01:04:28.880
is one that must not
weather the storm

01:04:28.880 --> 01:04:35.990
and be resilient, but also adapt
and prepare for climate change.

01:04:35.990 --> 01:04:38.870
Essential to this
work of adaptation

01:04:38.870 --> 01:04:43.640
is creating community-based
alternative models,

01:04:43.640 --> 01:04:46.430
which enables residents
to experiment,

01:04:46.430 --> 01:04:51.020
learn, and envision
a sustainable future.

01:04:51.020 --> 01:04:54.470
REAP's Grow or Die
campaign has successfully

01:04:54.470 --> 01:04:58.520
transformed four
city-owned vacant lots

01:04:58.520 --> 01:05:02.750
into multi-use community
gardens, where residents

01:05:02.750 --> 01:05:09.300
build community and develop
the skills in food cultivation.

01:05:09.300 --> 01:05:12.930
In the next year, we
will expand our vision,

01:05:12.930 --> 01:05:16.620
and engage in efforts to
promote long-term community

01:05:16.620 --> 01:05:19.660
land use and control.

01:05:19.660 --> 01:05:21.550
We believe this move
to our community

01:05:21.550 --> 01:05:24.700
control through
community land trusts

01:05:24.700 --> 01:05:29.170
will protest against unwanted
private development that

01:05:29.170 --> 01:05:31.780
drives the
gentrification, instead

01:05:31.780 --> 01:05:37.070
of supporting the stabilization
of our neighborhoods.

01:05:37.070 --> 01:05:42.720
As an anchor organization of
the Green Justice Coalition,

01:05:42.720 --> 01:05:48.060
one of ACE's goals is to lead
public education strategies

01:05:48.060 --> 01:05:52.500
to build legislator and public
support for clean energy

01:05:52.500 --> 01:05:56.100
and environmental protection.

01:05:56.100 --> 01:05:59.200
ACE leads Green Justice
Coalition's work

01:05:59.200 --> 01:06:01.240
on a landmark
environmental justice

01:06:01.240 --> 01:06:05.950
bill, an act relative
to environmental justice

01:06:05.950 --> 01:06:08.740
and toxic reduction.

01:06:08.740 --> 01:06:11.860
And the comment was,
which would incorporate

01:06:11.860 --> 01:06:15.070
a definition of environmental
justice community

01:06:15.070 --> 01:06:20.220
into the Massachusetts general
laws, required the development

01:06:20.220 --> 01:06:23.640
and implementation of
environmental justice policies

01:06:23.640 --> 01:06:27.040
across state
secretariats, and limit

01:06:27.040 --> 01:06:30.360
the setting of new
industrial facilities

01:06:30.360 --> 01:06:34.560
that rely on toxic materials
in environmental justice

01:06:34.560 --> 01:06:37.820
communities.

01:06:37.820 --> 01:06:40.430
Through our coalition
work, ACE effectively

01:06:40.430 --> 01:06:44.330
pushed Massachusetts to
enact its first statewide

01:06:44.330 --> 01:06:47.180
environmental
justice policy, which

01:06:47.180 --> 01:06:52.660
created a legal structure
necessary to combat and prevent

01:06:52.660 --> 01:06:56.360
the environmental overburdening
of low-income communities

01:06:56.360 --> 01:06:59.230
and communities of color.

01:06:59.230 --> 01:07:01.860
With an advocated and
negotiated approval

01:07:01.860 --> 01:07:05.140
of the state's three-year
energy efficiency

01:07:05.140 --> 01:07:10.420
plans, making visible the needs
of low income energy consumers

01:07:10.420 --> 01:07:12.620
and renters.

01:07:12.620 --> 01:07:17.180
In all of our environmental
justice organizing and advocacy

01:07:17.180 --> 01:07:22.070
work, we bring an intersectional
analysis connecting

01:07:22.070 --> 01:07:25.550
clean energy and
reduce greenhouse gas

01:07:25.550 --> 01:07:31.460
to greater equity and economic
livelihood, development plans,

01:07:31.460 --> 01:07:35.075
housing, and health outcomes,
and legal and technical

01:07:35.075 --> 01:07:35.680
expertise.

01:07:38.800 --> 01:07:41.160
Neighborhoods that
have seen decades

01:07:41.160 --> 01:07:45.300
of public and private
disinvestment,

01:07:45.300 --> 01:07:49.530
environmental degradation,
and racist segregation,

01:07:49.530 --> 01:07:52.230
are now being flooded
with an influx

01:07:52.230 --> 01:07:56.070
of new capital,
new developments,

01:07:56.070 --> 01:07:58.700
and new residents.

01:07:58.700 --> 01:08:03.250
A large part of this
problem is an over-reliance

01:08:03.250 --> 01:08:08.300
on the private sector,
and an overall agenda

01:08:08.300 --> 01:08:11.720
to drive urban development.

01:08:11.720 --> 01:08:16.899
The public sector sees its role
as facilitating and supporting

01:08:16.899 --> 01:08:22.609
private development through
public policy and spending.

01:08:22.609 --> 01:08:27.109
There is currently no greater
threat to Roxbury's culture

01:08:27.109 --> 01:08:31.319
and economicals
than gentrification,

01:08:31.319 --> 01:08:34.930
and the risk of
further displacement.

01:08:34.930 --> 01:08:39.779
The Roxbury campaign committee
is educating and organizing

01:08:39.779 --> 01:08:44.340
Roxbury residents around the
Boston Planning and Development

01:08:44.340 --> 01:08:45.979
Agency.

01:08:45.979 --> 01:08:47.790
the planning process
and development

01:08:47.790 --> 01:08:53.790
plans to ensure sustainable and
equitable community development

01:08:53.790 --> 01:08:56.250
in our neighborhoods.

01:08:56.250 --> 01:08:59.020
And our membership
program provides a space

01:08:59.020 --> 01:09:03.790
for our constituents to
identify problems and implement

01:09:03.790 --> 01:09:06.649
solutions.

01:09:06.649 --> 01:09:10.670
Our movement affirms
the rights of all people

01:09:10.670 --> 01:09:14.420
to public policy that
is free from any form

01:09:14.420 --> 01:09:18.840
of discrimination, to
participate as equal partners

01:09:18.840 --> 01:09:22.140
at every level of
decision making,

01:09:22.140 --> 01:09:25.260
and for communities
to not be subject

01:09:25.260 --> 01:09:28.840
to environmental extraction.

01:09:28.840 --> 01:09:32.080
This movement more
broadly affirms the rights

01:09:32.080 --> 01:09:35.890
of communities not to
be subject to extraction

01:09:35.890 --> 01:09:40.880
that also includes culture
and the local economy.

01:09:40.880 --> 01:09:45.830
In transitioning from an
extractive to adjusted economy,

01:09:45.830 --> 01:09:50.240
municipalities,
developers, and communities

01:09:50.240 --> 01:09:53.420
must work to
preserve and enhance

01:09:53.420 --> 01:09:57.230
local cultural and
economy assets.

01:09:57.230 --> 01:09:59.410
Thank you.

01:09:59.410 --> 01:10:00.895
[APPLAUSE]

01:10:11.800 --> 01:10:15.880
Hello, OK, so we're going
to shift gears a little bit.

01:10:15.880 --> 01:10:19.630
I am an environmental health
public health scientist.

01:10:19.630 --> 01:10:24.400
And so if we view many of
the environmental and social

01:10:24.400 --> 01:10:28.780
justice problems that my
colleagues have talked about

01:10:28.780 --> 01:10:32.350
today as nails, one
of my main hammers

01:10:32.350 --> 01:10:34.420
is the scientific method.

01:10:34.420 --> 01:10:37.000
And I'm probably more
comfortable talking

01:10:37.000 --> 01:10:39.670
in the language of data
and statistical models

01:10:39.670 --> 01:10:42.460
than I am storytelling--
so I'm actively

01:10:42.460 --> 01:10:45.812
resisting the urge of showing
you lots of graphs and data.

01:10:45.812 --> 01:10:47.830
[LAUGHTER]

01:10:47.830 --> 01:10:53.530
And rather, sharing
with you how I

01:10:53.530 --> 01:10:58.030
try to implement this
dual goal of conducting

01:10:58.030 --> 01:11:03.100
rigorous, innovative science
that actively addresses

01:11:03.100 --> 01:11:05.320
public health problems,
and that actively

01:11:05.320 --> 01:11:09.580
is used to promote health
protective policies,

01:11:09.580 --> 01:11:11.870
and support decision making--

01:11:11.870 --> 01:11:16.070
whether that's on the
local or national level.

01:11:16.070 --> 01:11:22.780
As Ajantha mentioned, I
seek to make advancements

01:11:22.780 --> 01:11:25.810
in science policy
and clinical practice

01:11:25.810 --> 01:11:27.850
to help secure
environmental justice

01:11:27.850 --> 01:11:33.942
and improve, unfortunately, the
growing inequalities in health.

01:11:33.942 --> 01:11:35.150
Particularly in our country--

01:11:35.150 --> 01:11:38.620
we're really moving in
the wrong direction.

01:11:38.620 --> 01:11:43.060
Instead of improving
things, even though we've

01:11:43.060 --> 01:11:45.190
been documenting a
lot of these health

01:11:45.190 --> 01:11:49.330
disparities for many
years, many decades.

01:11:49.330 --> 01:11:51.190
For the past 15
years, I've worked

01:11:51.190 --> 01:11:54.790
alongside various
community organizations

01:11:54.790 --> 01:11:57.550
using the scientific
method to both document

01:11:57.550 --> 01:12:00.610
and validate community concerns.

01:12:00.610 --> 01:12:04.000
I've addressed health
risks from various forms

01:12:04.000 --> 01:12:08.650
of environmental degradation,
ranging from poor indoor air

01:12:08.650 --> 01:12:13.030
quality in public housing
to ambient air pollution

01:12:13.030 --> 01:12:16.480
from oil refineries and
other polluting industries,

01:12:16.480 --> 01:12:19.480
metal-laden mine waste
at toxic Superfund

01:12:19.480 --> 01:12:22.640
sites on Native
American reservations,

01:12:22.640 --> 01:12:25.540
and most recently toxic
chemicals in beauty products

01:12:25.540 --> 01:12:28.540
marketed to women of color.

01:12:28.540 --> 01:12:31.570
I'm going to share a few
examples from my own research,

01:12:31.570 --> 01:12:38.030
and you'll probably see some
examples of scaling of issues,

01:12:38.030 --> 01:12:41.830
and the evolution of my own
work, which has been greatly

01:12:41.830 --> 01:12:44.530
influenced by listening
to community members,

01:12:44.530 --> 01:12:46.150
listening to collaborators.

01:12:46.150 --> 01:12:48.760
Also listening to
the data, and being

01:12:48.760 --> 01:12:52.310
willing to try new things.

01:12:52.310 --> 01:12:54.940
So the first example
I want to share

01:12:54.940 --> 01:12:58.240
with you comes from a
community-based participatory

01:12:58.240 --> 01:13:03.080
study, called the California
Household Exposure Study.

01:13:03.080 --> 01:13:05.230
This study was done
in collaboration

01:13:05.230 --> 01:13:07.930
with several
universities, and two

01:13:07.930 --> 01:13:12.100
community-based organizations,
including an EJ organization

01:13:12.100 --> 01:13:14.430
called Communities for
a Better Environment

01:13:14.430 --> 01:13:18.370
in the San Francisco Bay Area.

01:13:18.370 --> 01:13:20.140
The goal of this study--

01:13:20.140 --> 01:13:21.760
it was done in
northern California--

01:13:21.760 --> 01:13:26.530
and our main point was to
compare indoor and outdoor air

01:13:26.530 --> 01:13:29.140
pollution exposures
between Richmond--

01:13:29.140 --> 01:13:32.470
a neighborhood bordering an
oil refinery-- and Bolinas,

01:13:32.470 --> 01:13:36.910
a rural neighborhood that
served as a regional comparison.

01:13:36.910 --> 01:13:39.340
Something that was
unique about this project

01:13:39.340 --> 01:13:42.760
was, we had in many
different types of goals.

01:13:42.760 --> 01:13:45.190
So our scientific goal--

01:13:45.190 --> 01:13:48.250
and this was a project that
was funded by the National

01:13:48.250 --> 01:13:51.130
Institutes of Health-- so
our scientific goal was

01:13:51.130 --> 01:13:56.470
to characterize cumulative
impacts of various pollution

01:13:56.470 --> 01:14:00.310
sources in an environmental
justice community.

01:14:00.310 --> 01:14:02.980
Which we defined as
an area of low income,

01:14:02.980 --> 01:14:06.220
or ethnic minority residents,
who are disproportionately

01:14:06.220 --> 01:14:08.140
affected by pollution.

01:14:08.140 --> 01:14:10.450
We did this by measuring
numerous pollutants

01:14:10.450 --> 01:14:15.020
and assessing differences with
homes in non-EJ communities.

01:14:15.020 --> 01:14:16.790
In addition to our
scientific goals,

01:14:16.790 --> 01:14:20.170
we also had educational
and policy goals.

01:14:20.170 --> 01:14:22.240
Our educational
goals were to inform

01:14:22.240 --> 01:14:25.030
community members about
their air quality,

01:14:25.030 --> 01:14:29.380
and strategies for
exposure reduction.

01:14:29.380 --> 01:14:33.220
And then, one of our
main policy goals

01:14:33.220 --> 01:14:38.080
was actually to help our
advocacy partners inform

01:14:38.080 --> 01:14:40.660
local decisions about
the oil refinery.

01:14:40.660 --> 01:14:44.470
So those policy goals were
derived in collaboration

01:14:44.470 --> 01:14:46.910
with our advocacy partners.

01:14:46.910 --> 01:14:49.840
And so to help facilitate
those policy goals,

01:14:49.840 --> 01:14:51.620
we did a couple of things.

01:14:51.620 --> 01:14:55.090
One, we actively
reported the results back

01:14:55.090 --> 01:14:58.120
to the community in
various different ways.

01:14:58.120 --> 01:15:00.700
Too often, scientists come
into these communities,

01:15:00.700 --> 01:15:04.000
collect data, and then leave.

01:15:04.000 --> 01:15:07.130
There's never that return back.

01:15:07.130 --> 01:15:11.490
We held community events with
Spanish language interpreters,

01:15:11.490 --> 01:15:15.120
and child care, where
we gave the results back

01:15:15.120 --> 01:15:19.200
to the community in ways that
were culturally appropriate,

01:15:19.200 --> 01:15:21.840
at the appropriate
educational level.

01:15:21.840 --> 01:15:25.710
Which really also pushed us
to find new ways to visualize

01:15:25.710 --> 01:15:28.270
and communicate our data.

01:15:28.270 --> 01:15:33.090
We also reported individuals'
environmental exposure results

01:15:33.090 --> 01:15:36.600
back to them, if they had
requested that information.

01:15:36.600 --> 01:15:39.930
And at that time, that
was also very novel,

01:15:39.930 --> 01:15:42.480
because often
people think, well,

01:15:42.480 --> 01:15:46.170
if there aren't clear health
and safety thresholds, perhaps

01:15:46.170 --> 01:15:49.860
reporting the data back
will only create anxiety,

01:15:49.860 --> 01:15:52.770
or perhaps community
members won't know how

01:15:52.770 --> 01:15:55.230
to interpret that information.

01:15:55.230 --> 01:15:57.780
But we decided we would help
them in that interpretation

01:15:57.780 --> 01:15:59.970
process, and we
would we would let

01:15:59.970 --> 01:16:04.150
them make some of those
decisions for themselves.

01:16:04.150 --> 01:16:06.390
So these intentional
efforts helped

01:16:06.390 --> 01:16:08.610
to create a dialogue
and exchange

01:16:08.610 --> 01:16:10.260
with the local community.

01:16:10.260 --> 01:16:14.460
And it also led to a shared
ownership of the data.

01:16:14.460 --> 01:16:17.970
As a result, our community-based
organization partner

01:16:17.970 --> 01:16:20.400
presented the data to
the Richmond city council

01:16:20.400 --> 01:16:23.430
and planning commission,
and argued in court

01:16:23.430 --> 01:16:26.370
for a cumulative
impacts assessment

01:16:26.370 --> 01:16:30.390
to be included in the oil
refinery permit applications.

01:16:30.390 --> 01:16:33.750
And that was an approach that
was central to our research.

01:16:33.750 --> 01:16:36.510
This advocacy resulted
in a legal victory

01:16:36.510 --> 01:16:40.470
that actually blocked the
expansion of the oil refinery.

01:16:40.470 --> 01:16:45.370
So we saw that as a big
win for public health.

01:16:45.370 --> 01:16:49.980
Another kind of big I
guess lessen or component

01:16:49.980 --> 01:16:52.470
of this project
was the diversity

01:16:52.470 --> 01:16:54.570
of our scientific team.

01:16:54.570 --> 01:16:57.990
I think it also helped to
change how the community viewed

01:16:57.990 --> 01:17:00.600
scientists and science.

01:17:00.600 --> 01:17:03.990
Many communities of
color carry a distrust

01:17:03.990 --> 01:17:05.940
of science and medicine.

01:17:05.940 --> 01:17:10.320
In part because there's
been historical expectations

01:17:10.320 --> 01:17:13.650
of these communities by
the scientific enterprise.

01:17:13.650 --> 01:17:16.200
But also because
science and medicine

01:17:16.200 --> 01:17:19.620
are still commonly used to
discredit community knowledge

01:17:19.620 --> 01:17:21.690
and experience.

01:17:21.690 --> 01:17:23.370
You know, I did a
lot of the reporting

01:17:23.370 --> 01:17:26.010
back of the results
to the community,

01:17:26.010 --> 01:17:27.600
and I, probably
for many of them,

01:17:27.600 --> 01:17:30.600
I was the first woman of color
scientist that many of them

01:17:30.600 --> 01:17:31.930
had ever met.

01:17:31.930 --> 01:17:35.050
And I think that brings up an
important issue for this panel,

01:17:35.050 --> 01:17:38.700
which was very intentionally
created to lift up

01:17:38.700 --> 01:17:42.210
voices of women of color, about
why diversity and inclusion are

01:17:42.210 --> 01:17:43.140
important.

01:17:43.140 --> 01:17:46.290
Because it really does impact
what research questions are

01:17:46.290 --> 01:17:50.100
asked, the methods that
are used to answer them,

01:17:50.100 --> 01:17:55.800
as well as whose perspectives
and voices are included.

01:17:55.800 --> 01:18:01.110
Another side, another dimension
of the work that came out

01:18:01.110 --> 01:18:05.370
of that same community-based
participatory research project,

01:18:05.370 --> 01:18:11.160
involved more work on toxics
at the state and federal level.

01:18:11.160 --> 01:18:14.370
So another one of
our policy goals

01:18:14.370 --> 01:18:17.010
was to impact state
and federal policies

01:18:17.010 --> 01:18:21.440
regarding endocrine-disrupting
compounds in consumer products.

01:18:21.440 --> 01:18:23.170
So endocrine-disrupting
chemicals

01:18:23.170 --> 01:18:26.440
are substances
that are often are

01:18:26.440 --> 01:18:29.170
man-made industrial chemicals.

01:18:29.170 --> 01:18:32.290
They can interfere with how
hormones behave in our body,

01:18:32.290 --> 01:18:35.000
even at low levels.

01:18:35.000 --> 01:18:36.730
Many of these
chemicals are widely

01:18:36.730 --> 01:18:39.640
used in consumer products,
and consequently are

01:18:39.640 --> 01:18:41.860
ubiquitous in our
everyday environments,

01:18:41.860 --> 01:18:44.360
as well as in our bodies.

01:18:44.360 --> 01:18:48.200
So in this California
Household Exposure Study,

01:18:48.200 --> 01:18:53.340
we looked at a lot
of chemicals that

01:18:53.340 --> 01:18:58.910
may have come from vehicular
exhaust, or the oil refinery,

01:18:58.910 --> 01:19:02.430
but we also measured a
wide range of these EDCs.

01:19:02.430 --> 01:19:06.180
And we found very high levels
of PBDE flame retardants

01:19:06.180 --> 01:19:09.330
in all of the California homes.

01:19:09.330 --> 01:19:13.090
And they were some of the
highest levels in the world.

01:19:13.090 --> 01:19:15.750
And so this was kind of
a surprising finding,

01:19:15.750 --> 01:19:18.330
but we followed the data.

01:19:18.330 --> 01:19:22.530
And the back story on
these flame retardants

01:19:22.530 --> 01:19:23.970
are quite interesting.

01:19:23.970 --> 01:19:27.360
So beginning in
the 1950s and '60s,

01:19:27.360 --> 01:19:31.470
we started seeing a big
uptick in household fires,

01:19:31.470 --> 01:19:35.400
and fire-related
injuries and even deaths.

01:19:35.400 --> 01:19:39.210
And it was largely because
smoking rates were going up,

01:19:39.210 --> 01:19:41.730
lots of people were
smoking indoors, often

01:19:41.730 --> 01:19:44.070
falling asleep with
half-lit cigarettes.

01:19:44.070 --> 01:19:47.550
At the same time, we were
having more consumer products

01:19:47.550 --> 01:19:52.080
like furniture being made
from petrochemical byproducts,

01:19:52.080 --> 01:19:53.820
like polyurethane foam.

01:19:53.820 --> 01:19:59.250
So there was this perfect
storm of more smoking,

01:19:59.250 --> 01:20:00.810
and highly flammable products.

01:20:00.810 --> 01:20:04.740
Well, the tobacco
industry was very clever,

01:20:04.740 --> 01:20:08.335
because they very
cleverly shifted the focus

01:20:08.335 --> 01:20:10.710
from the cigarettes-- which
was really the main problem--

01:20:10.710 --> 01:20:12.030
to the couches.

01:20:12.030 --> 01:20:16.070
And they're like, those are
the things we have to fix.

01:20:16.070 --> 01:20:20.760
So it was a well-intentioned
intervention,

01:20:20.760 --> 01:20:23.640
but furniture makers
started treating furniture

01:20:23.640 --> 01:20:25.890
with these chemical
flame retardants, which

01:20:25.890 --> 01:20:27.715
they just mixed into the foam.

01:20:27.715 --> 01:20:29.090
And they thought
they were inert,

01:20:29.090 --> 01:20:31.215
and they thought they were
staying in the products.

01:20:31.215 --> 01:20:33.760
Well, lo and behold,
they weren't inert,

01:20:33.760 --> 01:20:35.937
they were actually
neurotoxicants.

01:20:35.937 --> 01:20:38.520
And they weren't staying in the
furniture-- they were actually

01:20:38.520 --> 01:20:43.140
migrating out of our products
into our dust and into our air.

01:20:43.140 --> 01:20:46.770
So we found-- jump
forward 30 or 40

01:20:46.770 --> 01:20:50.550
years, people had started
detecting them in breast,

01:20:50.550 --> 01:20:52.080
in house dust.

01:20:52.080 --> 01:20:56.340
And we found these very high
levels in California homes.

01:20:56.340 --> 01:21:01.230
And we hypothesized that it
was the unintended result

01:21:01.230 --> 01:21:06.870
of the very unique and stringent
fire safety standards that

01:21:06.870 --> 01:21:08.680
were unique to California.

01:21:08.680 --> 01:21:11.670
So they said that,
all furniture must

01:21:11.670 --> 01:21:14.710
be able to withstand an
open flame for 30 seconds.

01:21:14.710 --> 01:21:16.620
And so the way that
most furniture makers

01:21:16.620 --> 01:21:20.310
did this was by adding
these flame retardants.

01:21:20.310 --> 01:21:24.180
And so we wanted to
see, well, would we

01:21:24.180 --> 01:21:27.200
see the same thing
in people's bodies?

01:21:27.200 --> 01:21:29.760
And so we did several
other studies,

01:21:29.760 --> 01:21:33.060
and we actually found
that low-income,

01:21:33.060 --> 01:21:35.640
racially diverse pregnant
women in California,

01:21:35.640 --> 01:21:38.610
had some of the
world's highest levels

01:21:38.610 --> 01:21:41.520
of these PBDE flame
retardants in their bodies.

01:21:41.520 --> 01:21:47.250
And remember, these are
established neurotoxicants,

01:21:47.250 --> 01:21:51.960
based on studies in cells,
in animals, and even humans.

01:21:51.960 --> 01:21:54.900
So around this time this
research was published,

01:21:54.900 --> 01:21:59.190
California policymakers
started considering a change

01:21:59.190 --> 01:22:01.440
to the state's fire
safety standards.

01:22:01.440 --> 01:22:04.260
I happened to be doing
a post-doc in California

01:22:04.260 --> 01:22:08.190
at that time, so I testified
in front of the California

01:22:08.190 --> 01:22:12.780
legislature, and also
started writing commentaries

01:22:12.780 --> 01:22:15.060
to highlight the
disproportionate burden

01:22:15.060 --> 01:22:18.930
of chemical flame retardants
among low-income communities

01:22:18.930 --> 01:22:20.530
of color.

01:22:20.530 --> 01:22:23.800
And it was important
to highlight

01:22:23.800 --> 01:22:26.350
these disproportionate
impacts, but it was also

01:22:26.350 --> 01:22:30.970
important for
building coalitions,

01:22:30.970 --> 01:22:33.850
because up until that point,
the chemical industry had really

01:22:33.850 --> 01:22:38.110
tried to say, oh, this is
green legislation that only

01:22:38.110 --> 01:22:40.060
the enviro groups wanted.

01:22:40.060 --> 01:22:45.430
And they actually
tried to kind of pit

01:22:45.430 --> 01:22:50.890
the enviros against some of the
EJ and social justice groups,

01:22:50.890 --> 01:22:53.860
because still, low income
communities of color

01:22:53.860 --> 01:22:58.480
were dying more from
household fires.

01:22:58.480 --> 01:23:01.660
So during this
time, too, new data

01:23:01.660 --> 01:23:06.960
was coming, was being revealed
that these flame retardants

01:23:06.960 --> 01:23:10.740
really weren't that effective
in addressing the problem.

01:23:10.740 --> 01:23:16.350
So we started writing
about how you should really

01:23:16.350 --> 01:23:19.920
think about this fire
safety standard not just

01:23:19.920 --> 01:23:23.250
as an environmental standard,
but really a social policy.

01:23:23.250 --> 01:23:25.080
Because we know a lot
of these communities

01:23:25.080 --> 01:23:29.710
already face so many barriers to
healthy growth and development.

01:23:29.710 --> 01:23:33.480
So here is a chance
to prevent exposure

01:23:33.480 --> 01:23:35.950
to a known neurotoxicant.

01:23:35.950 --> 01:23:39.540
And over time, this
body of work has

01:23:39.540 --> 01:23:43.110
helped to change our approach
to fire safety at both the state

01:23:43.110 --> 01:23:46.560
and federal level, to
ensure adequate fire

01:23:46.560 --> 01:23:50.240
safety without the use
of hazardous chemicals.

01:23:50.240 --> 01:23:53.850
So now I just want to share
one last example, where

01:23:53.850 --> 01:23:57.390
my work is getting increasingly,
I would say, molecular.

01:23:57.390 --> 01:23:59.760
I'm becoming more
interested, and really trying

01:23:59.760 --> 01:24:04.020
to understand how
structural racism,

01:24:04.020 --> 01:24:08.970
and other systemic forces really
become biologically embedded

01:24:08.970 --> 01:24:12.690
at the molecular and cellular
level to affect health,

01:24:12.690 --> 01:24:17.820
and to also affect the
health of future generations.

01:24:17.820 --> 01:24:19.800
And some of this
work really lies

01:24:19.800 --> 01:24:21.990
at the intersection of
environmental justice,

01:24:21.990 --> 01:24:23.610
but also reproductive justice.

01:24:23.610 --> 01:24:28.650
Because a lot of it is really
about the right of women

01:24:28.650 --> 01:24:31.830
to control their
own bodies, and also

01:24:31.830 --> 01:24:34.230
to have control
over their ability

01:24:34.230 --> 01:24:38.160
to have a healthy
pregnancy, and to be

01:24:38.160 --> 01:24:42.620
able to raise their families in
healthy and safe environments.

01:24:42.620 --> 01:24:47.490
And some of this
work has been getting

01:24:47.490 --> 01:24:51.360
a lot of attention in the media
recently, just thinking about

01:24:51.360 --> 01:24:56.820
black women's health, and just
the really disturbing disparity

01:24:56.820 --> 01:25:01.500
around how many black women
are dying in childbirth today.

01:25:01.500 --> 01:25:05.040
You look at my own city of DC,
one of the most wealthy cities

01:25:05.040 --> 01:25:07.950
in this country, and our
maternal mortality rate

01:25:07.950 --> 01:25:10.530
is twice the national average.

01:25:10.530 --> 01:25:15.630
There's whole wards of DS
that lack a maternity ward.

01:25:15.630 --> 01:25:23.090
Which to me is completely
unacceptable in 2018 in USA.

01:25:23.090 --> 01:25:27.460
So I'm trying to connect
structural racism,

01:25:27.460 --> 01:25:29.560
and how it may become
biologically embedded

01:25:29.560 --> 01:25:31.820
to impact reproductive health.

01:25:31.820 --> 01:25:39.790
And so one way we're
doing that is we're

01:25:39.790 --> 01:25:42.040
starting to look at the
health repercussions

01:25:42.040 --> 01:25:45.850
of toxic chemicals in beauty
products through an EJ lens.

01:25:45.850 --> 01:25:48.600
Something we refer to as
the environmental injustice

01:25:48.600 --> 01:25:50.230
of beauty.

01:25:50.230 --> 01:25:52.780
Beauty products use is
an understudied source

01:25:52.780 --> 01:25:55.750
of environmental
chemical exposures.

01:25:55.750 --> 01:25:57.250
Some of these
products could include

01:25:57.250 --> 01:26:00.400
reproductive and developmental
toxicants, such as pthalates

01:26:00.400 --> 01:26:02.410
and heavy metals.

01:26:02.410 --> 01:26:07.690
However, disclosure requirements
are limited and inconsistent.

01:26:07.690 --> 01:26:09.970
Compared with white
women, women of color

01:26:09.970 --> 01:26:11.950
have higher levels
of beauty product

01:26:11.950 --> 01:26:14.720
related environmental
chemicals in their bodies.

01:26:14.720 --> 01:26:17.350
And this is independent
of socioeconomic status--

01:26:17.350 --> 01:26:22.510
so it can't be explained by
socioeconomic status alone.

01:26:22.510 --> 01:26:25.060
So it can't be
explained by class.

01:26:25.060 --> 01:26:28.420
Even small exposures to
these toxic chemicals

01:26:28.420 --> 01:26:32.020
during critical periods of
development, such as pregnancy,

01:26:32.020 --> 01:26:36.190
can trigger adverse health
consequences on fertility,

01:26:36.190 --> 01:26:40.870
on pregnancy, on brain
development, and even cancer.

01:26:40.870 --> 01:26:45.400
Mass distributions of images
that idealized whiteness can

01:26:45.400 --> 01:26:49.330
influence sales of hair
straighteners, skin lighteners,

01:26:49.330 --> 01:26:51.700
and odor-masking products.

01:26:51.700 --> 01:26:55.930
And racial discrimination
based on European beauty norms

01:26:55.930 --> 01:26:59.920
can lead to internalized racism,
body shame, and skin tone

01:26:59.920 --> 01:27:01.420
dissatisfaction.

01:27:01.420 --> 01:27:03.040
Factors that can
influence product

01:27:03.040 --> 01:27:08.560
use to achieve these
idealized beauty norms.

01:27:08.560 --> 01:27:13.600
So we are starting to look at
beauty products use as one way

01:27:13.600 --> 01:27:15.240
that structural
discrimination may

01:27:15.240 --> 01:27:17.920
become biologically embedded.

01:27:17.920 --> 01:27:21.484
And in one future project,
or upcoming project,

01:27:21.484 --> 01:27:22.900
we're actually
going to be working

01:27:22.900 --> 01:27:25.540
with a multi-disciplinary
team of public health

01:27:25.540 --> 01:27:29.170
scientists, social scientists,
as well as grassroots,

01:27:29.170 --> 01:27:34.360
EJ-RJ organizations to identify
links between beauty product

01:27:34.360 --> 01:27:38.860
use and racial ethnic
differences in breast cancer,

01:27:38.860 --> 01:27:44.500
through community-based surveys
and chemical product testing.

01:27:44.500 --> 01:27:49.690
In general, we're trying
to use sophisticated,

01:27:49.690 --> 01:27:54.640
emerging, biological
molecular tools,

01:27:54.640 --> 01:28:00.220
with nuanced social
structural frameworks

01:28:00.220 --> 01:28:03.820
to move beyond just
looking at race

01:28:03.820 --> 01:28:07.570
as this dichotomous
biological construct,

01:28:07.570 --> 01:28:11.080
to one that's really looking at
it more as a social construct,

01:28:11.080 --> 01:28:15.880
and really focusing on racism,
in addition to just race.

01:28:15.880 --> 01:28:20.600
So and all of this
research, I should say,

01:28:20.600 --> 01:28:25.060
has been a great opportunity
to train the next generation

01:28:25.060 --> 01:28:29.200
of women of color
scientists, and to get

01:28:29.200 --> 01:28:31.730
them engaged into this work.

01:28:31.730 --> 01:28:36.910
So it's kind of new models
of not only new disease

01:28:36.910 --> 01:28:41.920
models, but new ways
of creating knowledge.

01:28:41.920 --> 01:28:44.920
And I just want to end by
saying that, even though I often

01:28:44.920 --> 01:28:46.930
speak in the language
of data and numbers,

01:28:46.930 --> 01:28:50.920
good science alone is not
enough to create social change.

01:28:50.920 --> 01:28:54.130
I'm equally committed to
translating and disseminating

01:28:54.130 --> 01:28:58.910
the science for public
health policy and practice.

01:28:58.910 --> 01:29:02.272
So I'll just leave it at that.

01:29:05.236 --> 01:29:06.718
[APPLAUSE]

01:29:14.150 --> 01:29:15.040
That was wonderful.

01:29:15.040 --> 01:29:19.590
Thank you so much for those
incredible presentations.

01:29:19.590 --> 01:29:21.075
I just want to
open the floor up.

01:29:21.075 --> 01:29:23.230
You guys have all
been here listening,

01:29:23.230 --> 01:29:26.280
so I'm sure you have
lots of questions.

01:29:26.280 --> 01:29:29.680
I have questions of my own, but
I think let's start with yours.

01:29:29.680 --> 01:29:31.006
Yeah?

01:29:31.006 --> 01:29:32.455
[INAUDIBLE]

01:29:36.802 --> 01:29:39.683
Trina, I want to ask you a
question about the garden

01:29:39.683 --> 01:29:40.183
project.

01:29:40.183 --> 01:29:46.150
What are your hopes
for the project?

01:29:46.150 --> 01:29:48.730
How do you see this evolving?

01:29:48.730 --> 01:29:52.600
Well, that's a really
great question, thank you.

01:29:52.600 --> 01:29:57.490
I'm very interested in
the power of stories,

01:29:57.490 --> 01:30:03.100
and the power of culture,
and how we talk about change

01:30:03.100 --> 01:30:06.490
that is led by people who
are directly impacted.

01:30:06.490 --> 01:30:09.760
I'm also very interested
in black women's stories,

01:30:09.760 --> 01:30:15.160
black women as leaders,
black women as innovators,

01:30:15.160 --> 01:30:18.040
and thinkers, and scientists.

01:30:18.040 --> 01:30:24.430
And I just feel that black
people's relationship to land,

01:30:24.430 --> 01:30:29.905
because of the legacy
of enslavement,

01:30:29.905 --> 01:30:36.660
that that connection is really--

01:30:36.660 --> 01:30:41.550
and analyzing why
that connection

01:30:41.550 --> 01:30:45.225
is really important in terms
of our environmental activism.

01:30:49.290 --> 01:30:53.220
And I love gardening, and I have
lots of black women in my life

01:30:53.220 --> 01:30:55.710
who garden, and I love them
all, and I learn something

01:30:55.710 --> 01:30:57.100
from all of them.

01:30:57.100 --> 01:30:59.250
And I think that
just gardening are

01:30:59.250 --> 01:31:01.080
really interesting stories--

01:31:01.080 --> 01:31:04.650
they're ways of telling
stories about who we are

01:31:04.650 --> 01:31:07.260
and where we come from.

01:31:07.260 --> 01:31:09.880
And that's powerful to me.

01:31:09.880 --> 01:31:13.800
So I don't know if that's a
direct answer to your question,

01:31:13.800 --> 01:31:19.170
but I think there's a lot
to learn from black women

01:31:19.170 --> 01:31:23.390
environmental leaders
that we don't know.

01:31:23.390 --> 01:31:26.080
And I'm interested in those
stories being uplifted.

01:31:30.789 --> 01:31:32.330
Can you introduce
yourself, actually,

01:31:32.330 --> 01:31:35.594
before you ask your question?

01:31:35.594 --> 01:31:39.130
--sit on the back of this couch.

01:31:39.130 --> 01:31:41.960
I'm Amelia, I'm a
junior at the college.

01:31:41.960 --> 01:31:43.880
And I want to say
thank you to all of you

01:31:43.880 --> 01:31:47.630
guys-- this has been a
really fascinating panel.

01:31:47.630 --> 01:31:52.960
My question is about
the future, I guess.

01:31:52.960 --> 01:31:56.440
We've heard a lot about
the need for adaptation

01:31:56.440 --> 01:32:01.030
to climate change on both
macro and micro levels.

01:32:01.030 --> 01:32:02.800
But I'm wondering
what your thoughts are

01:32:02.800 --> 01:32:07.480
about how communities can
adapt, in terms of transforming

01:32:07.480 --> 01:32:11.170
themselves, and whether
environmental justice is also

01:32:11.170 --> 01:32:14.320
a project of
transforming communities

01:32:14.320 --> 01:32:15.340
to tackle the future?

01:32:21.350 --> 01:32:23.422
I think that's
addressed to any of you.

01:32:28.340 --> 01:32:30.257
I guess a couple of
things come up for me

01:32:30.257 --> 01:32:31.340
when I hear that question.

01:32:31.340 --> 01:32:38.270
I think climate
resiliency, the that term

01:32:38.270 --> 01:32:43.010
has been coming up a lot
in philanthropic spaces,

01:32:43.010 --> 01:32:45.770
and also in spaces
of organizing.

01:32:45.770 --> 01:32:50.000
And I think that one
of the lessons that

01:32:50.000 --> 01:32:52.640
was learned from
Hurricane Sandy,

01:32:52.640 --> 01:32:56.420
from Katrina, that I
think is important,

01:32:56.420 --> 01:32:59.840
is to understand that our
neighbors and our communities

01:32:59.840 --> 01:33:02.690
are also first responders.

01:33:02.690 --> 01:33:05.900
And so part of how
communities are able to adapt

01:33:05.900 --> 01:33:10.880
is by continuing to build
relationships with each other.

01:33:10.880 --> 01:33:18.110
And that sounds
sort of slow, but it

01:33:18.110 --> 01:33:21.740
is the thing that saves
people in those moments,

01:33:21.740 --> 01:33:26.570
is their ability to be
rescued, to be recognized,

01:33:26.570 --> 01:33:30.000
and to be connected
to a social network.

01:33:30.000 --> 01:33:33.860
And so I think
adaptation and resiliency

01:33:33.860 --> 01:33:37.550
is about the physical
infrastructure that

01:33:37.550 --> 01:33:42.730
gives people a few more
hours to get to a safe place,

01:33:42.730 --> 01:33:48.200
but it is also about, what
are the ways in which we

01:33:48.200 --> 01:33:50.930
need to have policies that
support and strengthen

01:33:50.930 --> 01:33:51.660
communities?

01:33:51.660 --> 01:33:54.950
Which is one of the reasons why
gentrification and displacement

01:33:54.950 --> 01:33:59.180
is such a huge threat to
communities that are already

01:33:59.180 --> 01:34:01.880
going to be less likely to
be able to be resilient,

01:34:01.880 --> 01:34:05.430
because people are moving away
from those social networks.

01:34:05.430 --> 01:34:11.540
I think it's also a reason
why jobs and economic policies

01:34:11.540 --> 01:34:16.340
are really important, because
the ways in which people

01:34:16.340 --> 01:34:18.750
have to have multiple jobs--

01:34:18.750 --> 01:34:21.350
so they're not at
home being able to be

01:34:21.350 --> 01:34:23.420
in those social
spaces because they

01:34:23.420 --> 01:34:26.120
have to work to pay their rent.

01:34:26.120 --> 01:34:27.740
And so I think all
of those things

01:34:27.740 --> 01:34:31.220
are really linked together,
and the environmental justice

01:34:31.220 --> 01:34:34.550
framework, I think,
provides analysis

01:34:34.550 --> 01:34:39.440
of how those different
problems are intersected

01:34:39.440 --> 01:34:43.052
and how we can think
about solutions.

01:34:43.052 --> 01:34:44.950
If I can just add--

01:34:44.950 --> 01:34:47.860
and I also would just say
that, communities of color

01:34:47.860 --> 01:34:49.990
have always adapted.

01:34:49.990 --> 01:34:54.070
And you don't survive 400
plus years of oppression,

01:34:54.070 --> 01:34:58.360
and not have strategies
for adapting.

01:34:58.360 --> 01:35:00.520
And so I feel like one
of our opportunities

01:35:00.520 --> 01:35:04.600
is to learn from what
people have always done,

01:35:04.600 --> 01:35:08.050
and that we don't
always take ideas from,

01:35:08.050 --> 01:35:10.810
as Ami's pointing
out in her work.

01:35:10.810 --> 01:35:13.150
That you don't always
lead with the ideas

01:35:13.150 --> 01:35:16.210
that comes from
outside the community.

01:35:16.210 --> 01:35:18.910
That you're actually
engaging the community

01:35:18.910 --> 01:35:21.580
on what they know already.

01:35:21.580 --> 01:35:25.450
And that becomes part of the
strategy that we all value.

01:35:25.450 --> 01:35:29.800
So we've always adapted,
everyone has always adapted.

01:35:29.800 --> 01:35:34.090
And of course, we
always have to be

01:35:34.090 --> 01:35:36.820
attentive to what's emerging,
but we've always adapted.

01:35:36.820 --> 01:35:45.790
So this narrative about
what do people need to do?

01:35:45.790 --> 01:35:47.920
What have people
always done that we

01:35:47.920 --> 01:35:50.530
can learn from, and
invest in those strategies

01:35:50.530 --> 01:35:52.006
and to actually support them.

01:35:58.950 --> 01:36:00.890
Thanks, thank you very much.

01:36:00.890 --> 01:36:02.270
This is great.

01:36:02.270 --> 01:36:04.792
I'm loving hearing
about all of your work.

01:36:04.792 --> 01:36:05.500
I was wondering--

01:36:05.500 --> 01:36:06.291
Introduce yourself.

01:36:06.291 --> 01:36:11.300
Oh, my name is Kaya, I'm
an anthropologist, as well.

01:36:11.300 --> 01:36:13.940
I was wondering if you could say
a little bit more, all of you,

01:36:13.940 --> 01:36:14.440
about--

01:36:14.440 --> 01:36:17.062
I feel like I heard you all
are doing really intersectional

01:36:17.062 --> 01:36:19.520
work, and I feel like I heard
a lot about the intersections

01:36:19.520 --> 01:36:22.610
of environmental justice,
housing justice, transit

01:36:22.610 --> 01:36:24.680
justice, and I'm wondering
if you could just

01:36:24.680 --> 01:36:27.200
say more about where criminal
justice fits into that?

01:36:27.200 --> 01:36:30.170
How you see your work
intersecting with mass

01:36:30.170 --> 01:36:33.470
incarceration, with effects
of that on the communities

01:36:33.470 --> 01:36:34.410
that you work in.

01:36:34.410 --> 01:36:36.920
And where you see
the opportunities

01:36:36.920 --> 01:36:39.556
for working on that.

01:36:46.970 --> 01:36:47.603
Anyone?

01:36:47.603 --> 01:36:49.103
I have a lot to say
on that, but I--

01:36:49.103 --> 01:36:49.790
[INAUDIBLE]

01:36:49.790 --> 01:36:51.774
[LAUGHTER]

01:36:54.080 --> 01:36:58.730
So in Roxbury, you
probably know that there

01:36:58.730 --> 01:37:00.680
are two police stations.

01:37:04.220 --> 01:37:10.370
It is one of environmental
concerns, too.

01:37:10.370 --> 01:37:16.730
If you look around, you see a
lot of elderly people, not too

01:37:16.730 --> 01:37:18.770
many young people.

01:37:21.900 --> 01:37:26.760
Also, on top of that,
some of the problems

01:37:26.760 --> 01:37:31.470
we identified in mass
incarceration was,

01:37:31.470 --> 01:37:36.060
within mass
incarceration itself,

01:37:36.060 --> 01:37:41.670
there is a form of environmental
justice problem there.

01:37:41.670 --> 01:37:47.780
In some of the
Massachusetts facilities

01:37:47.780 --> 01:38:01.380
that are hosting a lot of
incarcerated people of color,

01:38:01.380 --> 01:38:08.660
we identified that there is a
concern of contaminated water

01:38:08.660 --> 01:38:18.580
within the facility, and we
are working with some house

01:38:18.580 --> 01:38:23.120
expertise to identify,
and what it means.

01:38:23.120 --> 01:38:30.480
So if you see environmental
justice, the scope goes on.

01:38:30.480 --> 01:38:35.140
And for ACE, or any
environmental justice community

01:38:35.140 --> 01:38:40.030
that we have been
working, the shape

01:38:40.030 --> 01:38:43.415
and the form of the
struggle has been changing.

01:38:47.310 --> 01:38:56.460
We may have a few successes,
but definitely in the past 20

01:38:56.460 --> 01:38:59.460
years, they have changed.

01:38:59.460 --> 01:39:04.260
They have become more
complicated, structurally.

01:39:04.260 --> 01:39:12.950
So seeing environmental justice,
and the criminal justice,

01:39:12.950 --> 01:39:14.150
they are all connected.

01:39:18.450 --> 01:39:24.840
So for our organizing
work would be to see

01:39:24.840 --> 01:39:27.450
the structural problems--

01:39:27.450 --> 01:39:32.330
just saying, oh, this
is people of color,

01:39:32.330 --> 01:39:34.600
so they are impacted by this.

01:39:34.600 --> 01:39:38.230
But it's much deeper than that.

01:39:38.230 --> 01:39:45.990
So the movement of Black
Lives Matter is just not

01:39:45.990 --> 01:39:47.700
an open-air--

01:39:47.700 --> 01:39:56.510
some type of-- so it has been
around for many, many years,

01:39:56.510 --> 01:39:57.580
as you can imagine.

01:39:57.580 --> 01:40:02.280
But within a struggle,
there's another struggle.

01:40:02.280 --> 01:40:04.420
That's why I'm trying to say.

01:40:04.420 --> 01:40:08.550
And there is a lot of work
to be done, definitely.

01:40:08.550 --> 01:40:13.260
But finding those solutions
is what we should focus on.

01:40:13.260 --> 01:40:16.950
Because it seems
sometimes, it's endless.

01:40:19.470 --> 01:40:22.990
But yeah, if anyone
wants to add on that.

01:40:22.990 --> 01:40:27.270
Well, and sometimes
we know the solutions,

01:40:27.270 --> 01:40:30.420
but it's about implementing
basic solutions.

01:40:30.420 --> 01:40:33.000
So take the example of lead--

01:40:33.000 --> 01:40:36.540
we know the health
effects of lead.

01:40:36.540 --> 01:40:38.430
We know how to fix that problem.

01:40:38.430 --> 01:40:42.960
Whether it's lead in water,
or lead in lead paint.

01:40:42.960 --> 01:40:46.830
And yet, in some
ways, lead, like

01:40:46.830 --> 01:40:50.430
the problem of getting
blood levels down

01:40:50.430 --> 01:40:52.110
is considered a
public health victory,

01:40:52.110 --> 01:40:56.910
but really it's been
concentrated globally

01:40:56.910 --> 01:41:01.320
among poor people, and in this
country, and in EJ communities

01:41:01.320 --> 01:41:05.940
And we know that lead
exposures in children,

01:41:05.940 --> 01:41:07.440
they're irreversible.

01:41:07.440 --> 01:41:11.040
And they also affect
brain development,

01:41:11.040 --> 01:41:16.560
but they may also be
increasing violent behavior

01:41:16.560 --> 01:41:19.200
and things linked to--

01:41:19.200 --> 01:41:22.050
so they're almost
predisposing people

01:41:22.050 --> 01:41:26.320
to get into the
criminal justice system.

01:41:26.320 --> 01:41:30.180
So in that way, some of
these environmental concerns

01:41:30.180 --> 01:41:32.950
are perpetuating these cycles.

01:41:32.950 --> 01:41:35.700
And in the case
of lead, we don't

01:41:35.700 --> 01:41:38.040
have to go out and
hunt for a solution.

01:41:38.040 --> 01:41:40.320
We actually know
them pretty well.

01:41:40.320 --> 01:41:43.999
So it's about just
having the political will

01:41:43.999 --> 01:41:45.739
the implement what we know.

01:41:49.230 --> 01:41:50.626
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

01:41:50.626 --> 01:41:54.520
I would like to add something.

01:41:54.520 --> 01:42:32.430
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

01:42:32.430 --> 01:42:37.460
I think that criminal justice
and environmental justice

01:42:37.460 --> 01:42:38.600
are linked.

01:42:38.600 --> 01:42:41.090
Because when you look
at all of the bodies

01:42:41.090 --> 01:42:43.460
that live in our communities,
who are these bodies?

01:42:43.460 --> 01:42:44.960
Who are these people?

01:42:44.960 --> 01:42:46.400
And it's people of color--

01:42:46.400 --> 01:42:49.070
immigrants, black communities.

01:42:49.070 --> 01:42:50.990
And these are the
very communities

01:42:50.990 --> 01:42:55.410
that are being criminalized
specifically because they're

01:42:55.410 --> 01:42:58.980
black, and there's this
prejudice behind being black,

01:42:58.980 --> 01:43:03.300
or a person of color, or a
person that's an immigrant.

01:43:03.300 --> 01:43:15.930
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

01:43:15.930 --> 01:43:19.990
In my community where I
live, 65% are Latinos,

01:43:19.990 --> 01:43:23.750
and I see that a lot of young
people are being incarcerated.

01:43:23.750 --> 01:43:30.090
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

01:43:30.090 --> 01:43:32.670
And these young
people are also black,

01:43:32.670 --> 01:43:34.680
because even though
we're Latinos,

01:43:34.680 --> 01:43:36.460
Latinos are very diverse.

01:43:36.460 --> 01:43:41.860
And so there are
also black Latinos.

01:43:41.860 --> 01:43:43.140
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

01:43:59.730 --> 01:44:03.420
With the current
administration that we have,

01:44:03.420 --> 01:44:06.420
they're implementing
anti-immigrant laws

01:44:06.420 --> 01:44:09.270
that our communities
are suffering through.

01:44:09.270 --> 01:44:10.680
And it's not only
our communities

01:44:10.680 --> 01:44:13.980
that are being incarcerated,
but they're also being deported.

01:44:13.980 --> 01:44:26.880
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

01:44:26.880 --> 01:44:30.090
These policies are
separating our communities.

01:44:30.090 --> 01:44:33.180
And for a lot of our
communities, to be deported

01:44:33.180 --> 01:44:34.740
means to die.

01:44:34.740 --> 01:44:36.600
Because when they
arrived here, they

01:44:36.600 --> 01:44:40.930
were able to escape
that violent situation.

01:44:40.930 --> 01:45:00.540
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

01:45:00.540 --> 01:45:03.040
When we talk about
environmental justice,

01:45:03.040 --> 01:45:05.580
we are also talking
about criminal justice.

01:45:05.580 --> 01:45:08.020
And all sorts of
types of justice--

01:45:08.020 --> 01:45:10.040
human rights, just
basic human rights.

01:45:10.040 --> 01:45:12.270
It's not only about
having clean air

01:45:12.270 --> 01:45:15.000
but rather having the
right to live and to have

01:45:15.000 --> 01:45:15.810
a life of quality.

01:45:18.490 --> 01:45:19.442
Thank you.

01:45:24.690 --> 01:45:26.750
From the same couch, up front.

01:45:26.750 --> 01:45:30.129
Hi, I'm Shalonda Baker,
and I'm a professor of Law

01:45:30.129 --> 01:45:31.545
and Public Policy
at Northeastern.

01:45:31.545 --> 01:45:35.260
So it's good to see
you, Tenbit, here.

01:45:35.260 --> 01:45:38.440
So one of the successes of the
environmental justice movement

01:45:38.440 --> 01:45:42.550
has also been its downfall,
in terms of the gentrification

01:45:42.550 --> 01:45:45.130
that we see in communities
that have been,

01:45:45.130 --> 01:45:46.990
quote unquote, cleaned
up, and are now

01:45:46.990 --> 01:45:50.080
more inhabitable and safer.

01:45:50.080 --> 01:45:53.740
So I see environmental justice
as a really useful framework,

01:45:53.740 --> 01:45:57.430
and a theoretical tool, to
identify problems, and then

01:45:57.430 --> 01:45:58.900
remediate.

01:45:58.900 --> 01:46:01.060
But I think we're in
this really unique moment

01:46:01.060 --> 01:46:04.810
with the just transition, which
many of you have mentioned,

01:46:04.810 --> 01:46:06.820
to look at the
different intersections

01:46:06.820 --> 01:46:09.190
between gentrification,
and among climate

01:46:09.190 --> 01:46:11.260
justice and
environmental justice,

01:46:11.260 --> 01:46:13.930
as well, particularly in some
of the energy innovations

01:46:13.930 --> 01:46:16.230
that some of you mentioned.

01:46:16.230 --> 01:46:18.280
And I was just wondering,
more concretely,

01:46:18.280 --> 01:46:22.030
about the particular
policy opportunities

01:46:22.030 --> 01:46:27.490
to link the gentrification piece
and the threats to the home

01:46:27.490 --> 01:46:30.490
with innovations around
energy and energy democracy--

01:46:30.490 --> 01:46:33.550
I know that was mentioned by
Jennifer, and also Kalila.

01:46:33.550 --> 01:46:37.060
And so I don't know if there's
anything happening locally

01:46:37.060 --> 01:46:42.970
in Boston around home security,
and security of land, that

01:46:42.970 --> 01:46:45.250
could allow for this just
transition to happen,

01:46:45.250 --> 01:46:47.860
that doesn't further
jeopardize the communities

01:46:47.860 --> 01:46:50.990
that are already at risk
of losing their homes.

01:46:57.060 --> 01:46:59.640
I would say that--

01:46:59.640 --> 01:47:01.440
I wouldn't say that
people are necessarily

01:47:01.440 --> 01:47:03.100
already making those links.

01:47:03.100 --> 01:47:04.710
But hopefully we'll
be there, soon.

01:47:04.710 --> 01:47:07.800
But a couple of folks
had mentioned the idea

01:47:07.800 --> 01:47:09.840
of a community land trust.

01:47:09.840 --> 01:47:13.950
And so Dudley Street
Neighborhood Initiative

01:47:13.950 --> 01:47:16.900
convenes the greater
Boston land trust network,

01:47:16.900 --> 01:47:19.350
which includes
GreenRoots, and ACE,

01:47:19.350 --> 01:47:22.950
and several other community
organizations across the Boston

01:47:22.950 --> 01:47:26.610
area, who've combined
forces to try

01:47:26.610 --> 01:47:29.730
to push more broadly
the land trust movement.

01:47:29.730 --> 01:47:34.020
So some of those folks are
just starting land trusts,

01:47:34.020 --> 01:47:35.520
so they're in the
process of trying

01:47:35.520 --> 01:47:37.830
to actually acquire the land--

01:47:37.830 --> 01:47:41.160
which is particularly
challenging,

01:47:41.160 --> 01:47:44.850
in the case of Chinatown, for
example, one that there's not

01:47:44.850 --> 01:47:46.440
a lot of vacant land.

01:47:46.440 --> 01:47:49.980
But then OK, you
can afford to buy

01:47:49.980 --> 01:47:55.990
a triple decker for, I don't
know, $700,000 or something,

01:47:55.990 --> 01:47:56.490
let's say.

01:47:56.490 --> 01:47:59.670
But then you don't
have enough resources

01:47:59.670 --> 01:48:03.970
to keep it affordable for the
tenants that are in there.

01:48:03.970 --> 01:48:08.820
And so one of the things that
they are trying to push for

01:48:08.820 --> 01:48:12.090
is dollars from the
Community Preservation Act.

01:48:12.090 --> 01:48:17.490
So this was a policy that
Boston passed last year, that

01:48:17.490 --> 01:48:21.290
allows access for resources
for affordable housing,

01:48:21.290 --> 01:48:23.340
green space, and
historic preservation.

01:48:23.340 --> 01:48:26.940
So I think that's
one opportunity.

01:48:26.940 --> 01:48:32.100
Also talking with the
city about prioritizing

01:48:32.100 --> 01:48:35.340
land for disbursement
to land trusts.

01:48:35.340 --> 01:48:39.470
So there are still some
smaller parcels of land

01:48:39.470 --> 01:48:41.580
in the city of
Boston, particularly

01:48:41.580 --> 01:48:44.550
in Roxbury, Dorchester,
and Mattapan.

01:48:44.550 --> 01:48:49.860
So how do we prioritize
that public resources

01:48:49.860 --> 01:48:52.770
going for the public good?

01:48:52.770 --> 01:48:55.290
And there have been
examples of that recently,

01:48:55.290 --> 01:48:57.960
with Dudley Street
Neighborhood Initiative.

01:48:57.960 --> 01:49:03.091
So we acquired a commercial
property in Upham's Corner--

01:49:03.091 --> 01:49:05.340
one of the largest commercial
properties that the land

01:49:05.340 --> 01:49:06.365
trust ever acquired.

01:49:09.660 --> 01:49:13.200
Its design and planning
is being discussed

01:49:13.200 --> 01:49:16.710
as a part of the larger Upham's
Corner planning process.

01:49:16.710 --> 01:49:19.290
What I haven't seen
people do just yet,

01:49:19.290 --> 01:49:23.550
is to think about what are
the opportunities for energy

01:49:23.550 --> 01:49:28.380
efficiency, or a connection
on the land that we do have.

01:49:28.380 --> 01:49:30.240
I think, in part,
because people are just

01:49:30.240 --> 01:49:34.995
like, the land is so expensive,
how do we even just get it?

01:49:38.250 --> 01:49:44.430
But there is also kind
of simultaneously a push

01:49:44.430 --> 01:49:53.160
around codification
of climate resilient--

01:49:53.160 --> 01:49:55.110
basically climate
resilience policies

01:49:55.110 --> 01:49:57.540
around the building codes
within the city of Boston.

01:49:57.540 --> 01:50:01.670
So a lot of the things that
developers are doing are--

01:50:01.670 --> 01:50:03.720
they're not required
to do those things.

01:50:03.720 --> 01:50:07.590
And so perhaps there's an
opportunity to think about,

01:50:07.590 --> 01:50:10.740
not only should this land be
used for the public good--

01:50:10.740 --> 01:50:14.610
which we've defined broadly
as doing affordable housing--

01:50:14.610 --> 01:50:16.830
but what are the
opportunities to build

01:50:16.830 --> 01:50:20.615
in a more sustainable
and resilient kind of way

01:50:20.615 --> 01:50:21.990
by looking at the
building codes.

01:50:21.990 --> 01:50:24.330
So yeah, those are
a couple of things

01:50:24.330 --> 01:50:26.910
that folks are talking about.

01:50:26.910 --> 01:50:34.650
I've also heard about policies
for when subsidized housing is

01:50:34.650 --> 01:50:39.390
redeveloped, to push for
upgrading of air conditioning

01:50:39.390 --> 01:50:40.500
within those units.

01:50:40.500 --> 01:50:43.170
Because we know that
especially for communities

01:50:43.170 --> 01:50:45.420
that are way from the
coast, where there's just

01:50:45.420 --> 01:50:48.720
a lot of concrete,
heat is one of the ways

01:50:48.720 --> 01:50:52.740
that people are going to be
suffering, and probably dying,

01:50:52.740 --> 01:50:54.735
if they don't have access
to cooling centers.

01:50:57.350 --> 01:51:02.450
Can I just-- because
several of you

01:51:02.450 --> 01:51:07.335
talked about the land trusts,
and also about the micro-grid.

01:51:07.335 --> 01:51:10.710
So is there no link between
the land trust and micro-grid?

01:51:10.710 --> 01:51:12.320
Is that what you're saying?

01:51:12.320 --> 01:51:14.210
I'm saying it's really
just getting started.

01:51:14.210 --> 01:51:18.440
So the micro-grid
project, I think

01:51:18.440 --> 01:51:22.360
the award for that
came earlier this year.

01:51:22.360 --> 01:51:25.340
And so the land trust that
DSNI has, for example,

01:51:25.340 --> 01:51:27.300
has been around for
a couple of decades.

01:51:27.300 --> 01:51:29.720
So some new things
are being introduced

01:51:29.720 --> 01:51:33.500
into the conversation because
there are environmental justice

01:51:33.500 --> 01:51:36.200
organizations at the table,
like ACE and GreenRoots.

01:51:36.200 --> 01:51:39.200
But I would say
within the past six

01:51:39.200 --> 01:51:41.664
to eight months people are
beginning to explore those.

