01:52:56.970 --> 01:53:04.440
And creating a world,
imagining alternative futures,

01:53:04.440 --> 01:53:06.690
in a world of shared values.

01:53:06.690 --> 01:53:09.810
And I really think that there's
a huge potential in terms

01:53:09.810 --> 01:53:13.670
of indigenous rights, and
environmental justice rhetoric,

01:53:13.670 --> 01:53:15.420
and also restorative
environmental justice

01:53:15.420 --> 01:53:18.520
for all marginalized
communities.

01:53:18.520 --> 01:53:21.932
And so I was wearing if you
guys had more to say about that.

01:53:28.190 --> 01:53:31.130
One thing-- thank
you, very much,

01:53:31.130 --> 01:53:36.350
and for just even lifting
up this future of where

01:53:36.350 --> 01:53:39.810
we have shared values.

01:53:39.810 --> 01:53:46.830
You know, I think that part
of the power of storytelling,

01:53:46.830 --> 01:53:48.330
and in hearing each
other's stories,

01:53:48.330 --> 01:53:51.080
is that we start to build
empathy for each other.

01:53:51.080 --> 01:53:55.890
And I feel like that's a
really undervalued facilitator

01:53:55.890 --> 01:54:03.720
of how we might start to
create equity and justice.

01:54:03.720 --> 01:54:08.910
And so I think that
when we hear stories

01:54:08.910 --> 01:54:11.959
and we start to make connections
between our histories,

01:54:11.959 --> 01:54:14.250
and understanding that a lot
of what we're dealing with

01:54:14.250 --> 01:54:17.910
has been set up, there's
a historical precedent set

01:54:17.910 --> 01:54:21.240
in motion by certain
laws and policies

01:54:21.240 --> 01:54:23.680
that got us where we are today.

01:54:23.680 --> 01:54:29.560
And so I think that it's that
larger ecosystem of what you're

01:54:29.560 --> 01:54:34.480
saying, is how do
we lift up what

01:54:34.480 --> 01:54:41.140
is indigenous rights, what is
the community knowledge that we

01:54:41.140 --> 01:54:43.480
hold?

01:54:43.480 --> 01:54:46.360
I think that one point
that I'm taking away, just

01:54:46.360 --> 01:54:47.830
from your own
reflection, I think

01:54:47.830 --> 01:54:49.540
it's going to take an
intersection of all

01:54:49.540 --> 01:54:51.560
of those different strategies.

01:54:51.560 --> 01:54:55.360
And I think that the
strategy around policy,

01:54:55.360 --> 01:54:58.390
I think that is an area where
we're playing a little bit

01:54:58.390 --> 01:55:01.630
of catch-up, and we have to
really engage our folks on--

01:55:01.630 --> 01:55:03.370
what are the
policies on the books

01:55:03.370 --> 01:55:05.800
right now that
need to be changed?

01:55:05.800 --> 01:55:09.190
That are causing
harm, that many of us

01:55:09.190 --> 01:55:12.010
really don't know
that much about?

01:55:12.010 --> 01:55:16.720
And we have to politicize
folks about policies, and how

01:55:16.720 --> 01:55:19.100
we can change policies.

01:55:19.100 --> 01:55:21.430
And so I feel like
that's an area--

01:55:21.430 --> 01:55:24.380
whether it's around
land usage, or energy.

01:55:24.380 --> 01:55:27.310
And if I could just lift
up a couple of things

01:55:27.310 --> 01:55:30.880
that some of our
grantees are doing,

01:55:30.880 --> 01:55:35.020
we had a grantee
network in Rhode Island

01:55:35.020 --> 01:55:38.650
of immigrant workers that just
passed legislation at the state

01:55:38.650 --> 01:55:40.630
level in Rhode Island,
that recognizes

01:55:40.630 --> 01:55:42.670
worker-owned cooperatives.

01:55:42.670 --> 01:55:46.600
That had not been
recognized in the state

01:55:46.600 --> 01:55:51.071
of Rhode Island, worker-owned
cooperatives, as businesses.

01:55:51.071 --> 01:55:53.320
Which means that maybe they
can get some state funding

01:55:53.320 --> 01:55:53.820
to start.

01:55:53.820 --> 01:55:56.920
But that's a game
changer for people.

01:55:56.920 --> 01:56:01.720
Or even thinking about
the incarceration--

01:56:01.720 --> 01:56:03.670
that there was a
group of young people

01:56:03.670 --> 01:56:07.750
that passed the CSA Act in
Providence around police

01:56:07.750 --> 01:56:11.200
brutality, and mandating that
the police department keep

01:56:11.200 --> 01:56:14.350
data on who they stop and why.

01:56:14.350 --> 01:56:17.410
Because they were learning
that young people had these--

01:56:17.410 --> 01:56:21.010
after having interactions
with the police--

01:56:21.010 --> 01:56:24.070
that their names are in
these gang databases.

01:56:24.070 --> 01:56:26.700
And they had no idea why.

01:56:26.700 --> 01:56:29.140
And so parents didn't know,
the youth didn't know.

01:56:29.140 --> 01:56:31.300
They'd go to apply
for jobs and programs,

01:56:31.300 --> 01:56:33.597
and then these
records would come up.

01:56:33.597 --> 01:56:35.680
And it's like, how the
hell did they get in there?

01:56:35.680 --> 01:56:37.660
And they'd have these
interactions with the police,

01:56:37.660 --> 01:56:39.910
and the police would put
their names in the database.

01:56:40.690 --> 01:56:44.800
So they just passed
a law that changes

01:56:44.800 --> 01:56:49.750
that, where the police have
to be transparent about what

01:56:49.750 --> 01:56:52.060
they're doing when they
interact with youth of color.

01:56:52.060 --> 01:56:53.540
So this is what I'm saying--

01:56:53.540 --> 01:56:58.960
this is the multi-strategy,
policy-level engagement

01:56:58.960 --> 01:57:02.680
that we have to be on top of.

01:57:02.680 --> 01:57:05.440
So I think that that's one of
the opportunities that we have.

01:57:14.260 --> 01:57:15.480
Thank you so much.

01:57:15.480 --> 01:57:17.580
I really enjoyed
the conversation

01:57:17.580 --> 01:57:20.360
on different scales.

01:57:20.360 --> 01:57:23.430
My question emerges out
of some of the things

01:57:23.430 --> 01:57:24.900
around the
environmental justice,

01:57:24.900 --> 01:57:26.880
and moving more to
what Ami was talking

01:57:26.880 --> 01:57:29.970
around science and
production of knowledge

01:57:29.970 --> 01:57:32.160
on a scientific level.

01:57:32.160 --> 01:57:34.800
And I wanted to raise--

01:57:34.800 --> 01:57:37.470
that's my first question,
how do you really

01:57:37.470 --> 01:57:39.510
make those connections
more explicit?

01:57:39.510 --> 01:57:41.100
Because most of
the time, when we

01:57:41.100 --> 01:57:42.910
think from
environmental justice,

01:57:42.910 --> 01:57:46.260
immediately that knowledge
is degraded as being

01:57:46.260 --> 01:57:51.090
less, scientifically less
knowledgeable, or less

01:57:51.090 --> 01:57:54.220
insightful about innovation
and all that stuff.

01:57:54.220 --> 01:57:57.600
And so I think it may be
interesting to see, how do we

01:57:57.600 --> 01:57:59.610
have that conversation,
that it doesn't really

01:57:59.610 --> 01:58:01.860
become us versus them?

01:58:01.860 --> 01:58:04.020
Because for instance, I am--

01:58:04.020 --> 01:58:05.640
by the way, I didn't
introduce myself.

01:58:05.640 --> 01:58:08.880
I'm [INAUDIBLE],, I
teach in Toronto.

01:58:08.880 --> 01:58:11.160
I sent some of my
students to go into one

01:58:11.160 --> 01:58:14.190
of the communities,
which is like Chelsea,

01:58:14.190 --> 01:58:18.570
and they were shocked how the
corporations have come in,

01:58:18.570 --> 01:58:21.960
and making demands and
claims on the indigenous land

01:58:21.960 --> 01:58:25.650
in order to build their
own power plants there.

01:58:25.650 --> 01:58:27.900
While the indigenous
people have been struggling

01:58:27.900 --> 01:58:31.170
for more than 40 years
in this particular area

01:58:31.170 --> 01:58:33.180
to really say, we don't
want power plants,

01:58:33.180 --> 01:58:35.490
because it's
contaminating our waters,

01:58:35.490 --> 01:58:38.190
it's destroying our lives--
cancer rate is higher

01:58:38.190 --> 01:58:39.930
than any other community.

01:58:39.930 --> 01:58:41.790
So I'm wondering
if there is a way

01:58:41.790 --> 01:58:46.470
of speaking to that kind
of gap, if you will.

01:58:46.470 --> 01:58:47.680
So that's my first question.

01:58:47.680 --> 01:58:51.090
My second question because I'm
also an international relations

01:58:51.090 --> 01:58:55.920
professor, one of the big
issues that you guys brought up

01:58:55.920 --> 01:58:59.670
about energy and migration,
we saw Donald Trump just

01:58:59.670 --> 01:59:01.710
attacked Syria.

01:59:01.710 --> 01:59:03.330
And one of the
major issues there

01:59:03.330 --> 01:59:05.820
is foreign policy
and militarization.

01:59:05.820 --> 01:59:08.760
So I just wanted
to throw that out,

01:59:08.760 --> 01:59:10.800
because I think one
of the major issues

01:59:10.800 --> 01:59:13.590
here is like a lot of
resources, public resources

01:59:13.590 --> 01:59:18.120
end up going to militarization,
and basically stealing

01:59:18.120 --> 01:59:23.080
other people's land
and energy resources.

01:59:23.080 --> 01:59:28.200
So how do we make that global
connection more explicit?

01:59:28.200 --> 01:59:31.980
And I think in a way we can
speak about America as being so

01:59:31.980 --> 01:59:35.190
isolated, and the big empire--

01:59:35.190 --> 01:59:37.980
can kill anybody everywhere--
but I think it may be important

01:59:37.980 --> 01:59:41.550
for us to start thinking,
especially around migration,

01:59:41.550 --> 01:59:42.990
what are those connections?

01:59:42.990 --> 01:59:45.300
Because when you are
displacing refugees,

01:59:45.300 --> 01:59:50.180
they're coning here,
perhaps, or Europe,

01:59:50.180 --> 01:59:53.700
but with what implications
on environmental issues

01:59:53.700 --> 01:59:58.055
and scientific approaches
to understanding?

01:59:58.055 --> 01:59:59.672
The environmental destruction?

01:59:59.672 --> 02:00:01.932
Thank you.

02:00:01.932 --> 02:00:03.380
Sure, I can start.

02:00:03.380 --> 02:00:08.420
I think your point is well
taken about the production

02:00:08.420 --> 02:00:13.200
of knowledge, and how
to engage communities

02:00:13.200 --> 02:00:15.050
and to lift up their knowledge.

02:00:15.050 --> 02:00:18.620
Especially to protect
their environment,

02:00:18.620 --> 02:00:19.600
protect their rights.

02:00:19.600 --> 02:00:24.060
And I think conversations
like this are very important.

02:00:24.060 --> 02:00:27.230
And I think it starts
with developing

02:00:27.230 --> 02:00:29.690
trust among different people--

02:00:29.690 --> 02:00:33.740
investing in these
relationships.

02:00:33.740 --> 02:00:38.810
I think everything starts
with relationships.

02:00:38.810 --> 02:00:40.980
And that gets back to
what Trina was saying,

02:00:40.980 --> 02:00:44.570
and especially relationships
across difference.

02:00:44.570 --> 02:00:47.400
And then once you have
those relationships,

02:00:47.400 --> 02:00:52.050
to be creative about
what you produce,

02:00:52.050 --> 02:00:55.350
and also the different
languages you

02:00:55.350 --> 02:00:57.180
can use in your
production, and also

02:00:57.180 --> 02:00:59.250
the different types of output.

02:00:59.250 --> 02:01:02.430
So language is being
anything from English

02:01:02.430 --> 02:01:07.470
to indigenous languages,
to more scientific,

02:01:07.470 --> 02:01:09.810
quantitative
language, to something

02:01:09.810 --> 02:01:13.620
that's very much
constructed to move policy.

02:01:13.620 --> 02:01:16.440
Which is, in and of
itself, its own language.

02:01:16.440 --> 02:01:20.910
Or a language that's
very much constructed

02:01:20.910 --> 02:01:25.620
to increase everybody's
awareness of a problem, which

02:01:25.620 --> 02:01:28.110
often means policy.

02:01:28.110 --> 02:01:30.780
So really thinking about--

02:01:30.780 --> 02:01:33.390
in a sense, I think, to
create change, a lot of us

02:01:33.390 --> 02:01:38.250
have to almost think
bilingually, but not

02:01:38.250 --> 02:01:45.210
necessarily thinking about
language in a looser term.

02:01:45.210 --> 02:01:51.000
Because I think
community-based partnerships

02:01:51.000 --> 02:01:54.070
can take many different forms.

02:01:54.070 --> 02:01:59.760
But I think that the best
ones recognize the fact

02:01:59.760 --> 02:02:01.920
that different stakeholders
have different needs,

02:02:01.920 --> 02:02:06.120
and ideally we'd be trying
to address some of these.

02:02:08.266 --> 02:02:10.140
Kind of going back to
your point about moving

02:02:10.140 --> 02:02:12.250
policy, two things--

02:02:12.250 --> 02:02:14.100
I've started to
get more into that.

02:02:14.100 --> 02:02:16.990
And it is a very
different way of thinking,

02:02:16.990 --> 02:02:19.470
and a different way of
translating information.

02:02:19.470 --> 02:02:24.120
And also asking very specific
questions that may be different

02:02:24.120 --> 02:02:26.490
sometimes the most
pressing questions

02:02:26.490 --> 02:02:27.910
for the scientific community.

02:02:27.910 --> 02:02:30.150
But then, I think the
other elephant in the room

02:02:30.150 --> 02:02:35.630
is, what is our
likelihood of changing

02:02:35.630 --> 02:02:38.070
policy for the better
on the federal landscape

02:02:38.070 --> 02:02:39.555
in the next few years?

02:02:39.555 --> 02:02:43.410
So even if that's what we
need to do, if you look at,

02:02:43.410 --> 02:02:48.830
in the space human rights
environment, public health,

02:02:48.830 --> 02:02:51.750
likely, the only thing, it
anything that's happening,

02:02:51.750 --> 02:02:56.080
is going strikingly in
the wrong direction.

02:02:56.080 --> 02:03:01.470
And so what are the
strategies in the face of that

02:03:01.470 --> 02:03:03.390
the big elephant in the room?

02:03:03.390 --> 02:03:06.720
But that also speaks to
different levels of government.

02:03:06.720 --> 02:03:10.380
So it's not that all the levels
of government line up neatly.

02:03:10.380 --> 02:03:12.000
So you've got
California, which is

02:03:12.000 --> 02:03:15.180
at war with the federal
government right now.

02:03:15.180 --> 02:03:17.370
So it's not just
about figuring out

02:03:17.370 --> 02:03:19.500
the language of policy,
and how to navigate

02:03:19.500 --> 02:03:22.190
the world of policy, but
at what level of state--

02:03:26.020 --> 02:03:28.330
you pitch your claims.

02:03:28.330 --> 02:03:31.090
And you can even use tensions
between different levels

02:03:31.090 --> 02:03:33.370
of government to your advantage.

02:03:38.640 --> 02:03:41.250
I heard a lot about
the municipal level.

02:03:41.250 --> 02:03:45.030
And that level of government
having a little more

02:03:45.030 --> 02:03:48.460
give, that it's a much more--

02:03:48.460 --> 02:03:51.230
there's possibilities
for participation.

02:03:51.230 --> 02:03:56.720
There's possibilities to lay
claim to policy as a right.

02:03:56.720 --> 02:03:59.000
I don't know whether
it's that easy

02:03:59.000 --> 02:04:01.452
to do at the federal level.

02:04:09.590 --> 02:04:12.240
Were all like, so
many things to say.

02:04:12.240 --> 02:04:16.380
I think you're right--

02:04:16.380 --> 02:04:19.020
a lot of us are mostly
contesting for power

02:04:19.020 --> 02:04:21.240
at the municipal
level, because that

02:04:21.240 --> 02:04:28.220
is where it's a level
that our base understands,

02:04:28.220 --> 02:04:30.180
and can vision around.

02:04:30.180 --> 02:04:33.020
And at the same
time, I also believe

02:04:33.020 --> 02:04:35.630
that this is part of the
reason why I was talking

02:04:35.630 --> 02:04:38.130
about this 10-year agenda.

02:04:38.130 --> 02:04:41.900
So part of the reason--

02:04:41.900 --> 02:04:47.030
I should say, we're not in this
position as a country because

02:04:47.030 --> 02:04:49.130
of this one election.

02:04:49.130 --> 02:04:57.980
So there were a series of
decisions and power strategies

02:04:57.980 --> 02:04:59.900
that folks had been
planning decades

02:04:59.900 --> 02:05:04.520
before this moment that happened
to come to fruition, maybe by--

02:05:04.520 --> 02:05:09.470
who knows, just as a
cloud of circumstances

02:05:09.470 --> 02:05:10.640
brought us to that.

02:05:10.640 --> 02:05:17.900
And so I think for me, that
means that we, our side,

02:05:17.900 --> 02:05:20.210
needs to also be doing
that kind of level

02:05:20.210 --> 02:05:21.830
of planning and strategy.

02:05:21.830 --> 02:05:22.640
Not that it's easy.

02:05:26.820 --> 02:05:29.600
But the hard part
is, not only being

02:05:29.600 --> 02:05:34.040
able to say what we don't want,
but really doing the hardware

02:05:34.040 --> 02:05:36.290
to vision about what
does it look like when

02:05:36.290 --> 02:05:37.370
we're going to govern?

02:05:37.370 --> 02:05:41.640
And how do we actually want
these systems transformed?

02:05:41.640 --> 02:05:45.110
And I think that's
the part that we

02:05:45.110 --> 02:05:49.520
have to really begin thinking
and strategizing about.

02:05:49.520 --> 02:05:54.590
And unfortunately, understanding
and grappling with the fact

02:05:54.590 --> 02:05:56.330
that, during this
period, there's

02:05:56.330 --> 02:05:58.700
going to be a lot of harm.

02:05:58.700 --> 02:06:00.780
That is just inevitable.

02:06:00.780 --> 02:06:05.690
And so how can we also
strengthen our practices

02:06:05.690 --> 02:06:08.900
for healing with each
other, and dealing

02:06:08.900 --> 02:06:12.500
with the multitudes
of many faceted ways

02:06:12.500 --> 02:06:16.220
that trauma is going to be
continuing to attack our folks,

02:06:16.220 --> 02:06:18.260
and is already is already here.

02:06:18.260 --> 02:06:22.430
But yeah, I think we have to
do you longer term visioning

02:06:22.430 --> 02:06:25.360
and planning.

02:06:25.360 --> 02:06:27.645
Does anyone want to answer
the militarism question?

02:06:32.770 --> 02:06:43.104
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

02:06:43.104 --> 02:06:45.020
Something that was very
interesting about what

02:06:45.020 --> 02:06:49.562
you had mentioned was that
intersection between what

02:06:49.562 --> 02:06:51.020
is happening here,
and also what is

02:06:51.020 --> 02:06:52.660
happening in other countries.

02:06:52.660 --> 02:06:54.730
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

02:07:03.800 --> 02:07:07.190
I think that when we talk
about environmental justice,

02:07:07.190 --> 02:07:09.770
we also have to talk
about capitalism

02:07:09.770 --> 02:07:14.060
and the economic system that we
have, that is, quite frankly,

02:07:14.060 --> 02:07:14.990
destroying our lives.

02:07:19.032 --> 02:07:20.380
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

02:07:41.237 --> 02:07:42.820
I'm going to talk
about Latin America,

02:07:42.820 --> 02:07:45.460
because that's what
has been my experience,

02:07:45.460 --> 02:07:47.710
and that's what I'm most
knowledgeable about.

02:07:47.710 --> 02:07:49.310
But we have suffered.

02:07:49.310 --> 02:07:52.220
We have suffered for
a very long time--

02:07:52.220 --> 02:07:58.460
ever since the colonialism
of extractivism.

02:07:58.460 --> 02:08:01.840
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

02:08:01.840 --> 02:08:05.980
And now we're living
through capitalism.

02:08:05.980 --> 02:08:11.830
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

02:08:11.830 --> 02:08:13.900
And so what connections
do we see there,

02:08:13.900 --> 02:08:16.960
between everything that is
economic and the environment?

02:08:16.960 --> 02:08:18.680
And it's completely connected.

02:08:18.680 --> 02:08:19.800
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

02:08:28.480 --> 02:08:30.820
And it's these
large corporations

02:08:30.820 --> 02:08:36.610
that go to our
countries, that just

02:08:36.610 --> 02:08:39.660
exploit our natural resources.

02:08:39.660 --> 02:08:40.750
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

02:09:03.970 --> 02:09:06.700
These major corporations,
by exploiting

02:09:06.700 --> 02:09:09.940
our natural resources, are
displacing indigenous groups,

02:09:09.940 --> 02:09:11.740
are displacing
basically everything

02:09:11.740 --> 02:09:13.120
that gets in their way.

02:09:13.120 --> 02:09:14.920
They're contaminating
rivers, they're

02:09:14.920 --> 02:09:17.500
taking our precious
goods, and it's exactly

02:09:17.500 --> 02:09:22.600
this system that is causing
this climate change.

02:09:22.600 --> 02:09:23.860
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

02:09:24.670 --> 02:09:27.440
And they do it there,
and they do it here.

02:09:27.440 --> 02:09:28.570
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

02:09:50.830 --> 02:09:53.590
So when you talk
about these systems

02:09:53.590 --> 02:09:55.330
and how they're
connected, we also

02:09:55.330 --> 02:09:57.430
have to talk about immigration.

02:09:57.430 --> 02:10:00.850
Immigration here, when we
talk about these poor people

02:10:00.850 --> 02:10:03.580
from Latin America,
from Central America,

02:10:03.580 --> 02:10:08.950
coming here, these ragamuffins
and riffraff that's immigrating

02:10:08.950 --> 02:10:10.772
into the United States--

02:10:10.772 --> 02:10:12.730
when we look at all of
that, we're not actually

02:10:12.730 --> 02:10:17.230
looking at what the problem
is, what the problem there is.

02:10:17.230 --> 02:10:18.550
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

02:10:19.660 --> 02:10:22.430
So we're not looking at
the root of the problem.

02:10:22.430 --> 02:10:23.840
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

02:10:26.762 --> 02:10:28.720
A lot of people think
that immigrants come here

02:10:28.720 --> 02:10:30.000
to take our jobs.

02:10:30.000 --> 02:10:31.480
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

02:10:31.480 --> 02:10:33.620
That we're criminals.

02:10:33.620 --> 02:10:45.740
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

02:10:45.740 --> 02:10:50.150
In 1998, Central America
suffered a hurricane

02:10:50.150 --> 02:10:53.000
that completely devastated
the region, which

02:10:53.000 --> 02:10:55.530
was called hurricane Mitch.

02:10:55.530 --> 02:11:00.590
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

02:11:00.590 --> 02:11:02.630
And that caused many
Central Americans

02:11:02.630 --> 02:11:05.850
to cross the border
into the United States.

02:11:05.850 --> 02:11:07.110
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

02:11:27.200 --> 02:11:32.600
And so as a result, we had
what is now called TPS--

02:11:32.600 --> 02:11:35.990
or temporary protective status.

02:11:35.990 --> 02:11:59.630
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

02:11:59.630 --> 02:12:03.170
So for years, these people
have lived here in the United

02:12:03.170 --> 02:12:07.400
States-- both Central American
and people from Africa--

02:12:07.400 --> 02:12:09.950
under this temporary
protective status.

02:12:09.950 --> 02:12:12.140
But now that temporary
protective status

02:12:12.140 --> 02:12:14.660
is being threatened,
and now they

02:12:14.660 --> 02:12:16.430
are being threatened
that they're

02:12:16.430 --> 02:12:20.370
going to now be stripped of the
TPS and live here illegally.

02:12:20.370 --> 02:12:26.360
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

02:12:26.360 --> 02:12:30.550
So for many Central Americans,
next year will be their last.

02:12:30.550 --> 02:12:31.640
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

02:12:49.390 --> 02:12:52.090
So when you look
at it, immigration

02:12:52.090 --> 02:12:56.170
is completely linked with
environmental justice.

02:12:56.170 --> 02:12:58.240
How is it connected
to capitalism?

02:12:58.240 --> 02:13:00.400
How is it connected
to climate change?

02:13:00.400 --> 02:13:02.840
Everything is absolutely
interconnected.

